export const coreJavaInterviewTopics: InterviewTopic[] = [
  {
    id: "basics",
    title: "Java Basics",
    icon: "☕",
    questions: [
      { id:"b1", question:"What is Java? What are its main features?", answer:"Java is a high-level, class-based, object-oriented programming language developed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems in 1995 and now owned by Oracle. It follows the WORA (Write Once Run Anywhere) principle — compiled Java code (bytecode) can run on any platform that has a JVM without recompilation. Java achieves platform independence through its two-step execution model: source code (.java) is compiled by javac into bytecode (.class), which is then interpreted or JIT-compiled by the JVM into native machine code at runtime.\n\nCore Features in Depth:\n1. Platform Independent: Java source compiles to bytecode, not platform-specific machine code. The JVM abstracts the underlying OS and hardware, so the same .class file runs on Windows, Linux, macOS, or any JVM-equipped system.\n2. Object-Oriented: Everything in Java (except primitives) is an object. It supports encapsulation, inheritance, polymorphism, and abstraction, enabling modular, reusable, and maintainable code.\n3. Simple: Java eliminated complex features from C++ like explicit pointers, operator overloading, and multiple inheritance (replaced by interfaces). Automatic garbage collection frees developers from manual memory management.\n4. Secure: Java's security model includes bytecode verification (checks for illegal code before execution), a sandbox model for applets, no explicit pointer arithmetic, and the Security Manager for runtime access control.\n5. Robust: Java emphasizes compile-time error checking (strong typing), runtime exception handling, automatic garbage collection (no memory leaks from forgotten deallocation), and null-reference checking at runtime.\n6. Multithreaded: Built-in thread support via the java.lang.Thread class and java.util.concurrent package. Threads share the same memory space, enabling lightweight concurrent execution without OS-level processes.\n7. Architecture Neutral: Primitive data types have fixed sizes across all platforms (int is always 32-bit, long is always 64-bit), unlike C/C++ where sizes vary by platform.\n8. High Performance: The Just-In-Time (JIT) compiler in the JVM identifies frequently executed bytecode (hot spots) and compiles them to native machine code, approaching C/C++ performance for long-running applications.\n9. Distributed: Java has built-in networking support (java.net package) and RMI (Remote Method Invocation) for distributed computing.\n10. Dynamic: Java supports dynamic loading of classes at runtime and dynamic memory allocation, enabling adaptive and extensible applications.", code:`public class HelloWorld {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        System.out.println("Hello, Java!");\n    }\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Key features: Platform Independent (bytecode on JVM), Object-Oriented, Simple (no pointers), Secure (bytecode verification), Robust (exception handling, GC), Multithreaded, Architecture Neutral (fixed primitive sizes), High Performance (JIT)." },
      { id:"b2", question:"Difference between JDK, JRE, and JVM?", answer:"JDK (Java Development Kit) is the full-featured development environment for building Java applications. It includes the JRE plus development tools like javac (compiler), java (launcher), jar (archiver), javadoc (documentation generator), and jdb (debugger). The JDK is what developers install to write and compile Java programs.\n\nJRE (Java Runtime Environment) is the minimum environment required to RUN Java applications. It consists of the JVM plus core class libraries (rt.jar, charsets.jar, etc.) and supporting files. End-users who only need to run Java applications install the JRE, not the JDK. The JRE cannot compile Java source code.\n\nJVM (Java Virtual Machine) is the abstract computing machine that executes bytecode. It is the runtime engine that converts .class bytecode into machine-specific code. The JVM performs: class loading (via ClassLoader subsystem), bytecode verification (via Bytecode Verifier), memory management (heap, stack, method area), garbage collection, and JIT compilation. The JVM is platform-specific — there is a different JVM implementation for Windows, Linux, macOS, etc. — but all execute the same bytecode.\n\nRelationship: JDK ⊃ JRE ⊃ JVM. The JDK contains the JRE which contains the JVM. You need JDK to develop, JRE to run, and JVM is the actual execution engine inside both.", code:`JDK = JRE + Dev Tools (javac, jar, javadoc)\nJRE = JVM + Core Libraries\nJVM = Bytecode Executor`, codeLanguage:"plaintext", explanation:"JVM converts bytecode→machine code. JRE=JVM+libraries (minimum to RUN). JDK=JRE+dev tools (required to DEVELOP). Relationship: JDK ⊃ JRE ⊃ JVM." },
      { id:"b3", question:"What is bytecode in Java?", answer:"Bytecode is the intermediate representation of Java source code produced by the javac compiler. It is a set of instructions (opcodes) for the JVM — not for any specific hardware CPU. When you compile a .java file, javac translates the source into one or more .class files containing bytecode. This bytecode is the key to Java's platform independence: the same .class file can be executed on any operating system that has a compatible JVM implementation.\n\nBytecode is stored in .class files using a compact binary format defined by the JVM specification. Each instruction consists of a one-byte opcode followed by zero or more operands. There are approximately 200 bytecode instructions covering operations like loading/storing variables, arithmetic, object creation, method invocation, control flow, and type casting.\n\nThe execution flow: .java source → javac compiler → .class bytecode → JVM class loader → bytecode verifier (security check) → interpreter or JIT compiler → native machine code → CPU executes. The JIT (Just-In-Time) compiler monitors which bytecode is executed frequently (hot spots) and compiles those sections to optimized native machine code, dramatically improving performance over pure interpretation.\n\nBytecode verification is a critical security feature: before any bytecode is executed, the JVM's verifier ensures it adheres to type safety rules, doesn't violate access restrictions, doesn't cause stack overflows/underflows, and performs correct type conversions. This prevents malicious or corrupted code from compromising the JVM.", code:`.java → javac → .class (bytecode) → JVM → machine code`, codeLanguage:"plaintext", explanation:"Same .class runs on any OS with JVM. Bytecode is verified before execution (security). JIT compiler optimizes at runtime (performance)." },
      { id:"b4", question:"Difference between path and classpath?", answer:"PATH is an operating system environment variable that tells the OS where to find executable programs. When you type 'javac' or 'java' in the command line, the OS searches the directories listed in PATH to find these executables. Setting PATH to include the JDK's bin directory (e.g., C:\\jdk-17\\bin on Windows or /usr/lib/jvm/java-17/bin on Linux) allows you to run Java tools from any directory without typing the full path. PATH is OS-level and has nothing to do with Java specifically — it works the same way for any executable program.\n\nCLASSPATH is a Java-specific environment variable (or JVM command-line option using -cp or -classpath) that tells the JVM where to find user-defined classes and packages during runtime. When the JVM needs to load a class (e.g., com.myapp.Utils), it searches the directories and JAR files listed in CLASSPATH. The default classpath is the current directory ('.'). You can specify multiple paths using the path separator (';' on Windows, ':' on Unix).\n\nKey differences: PATH is used by the OS to find executables BEFORE Java runs. CLASSPATH is used by the JVM to find classes AFTER Java starts. PATH points to bin directories containing .exe/.sh files. CLASSPATH points to directories containing .class files and .jar files. If you get 'javac is not recognized', fix PATH. If you get 'ClassNotFoundException' or 'NoClassDefFoundError', fix CLASSPATH.\n\nModern practice: Use the -cp flag (java -cp .:lib/* com.myapp.Main) instead of setting a global CLASSPATH environment variable, as the global variable can cause conflicts between different Java projects.", code:`PATH=C:\\jdk-17\\bin (OS level)\nCLASSPATH=.;C:\\lib\\* (JVM level)`, codeLanguage:"shell", explanation:"PATH is for the OS to find JDK tools. CLASSPATH is for the JVM to find your .class files and JARs. '.' means current directory." },
      { id:"b5", question:"Why is Java not 100% object-oriented?", answer:"Java is not purely object-oriented because it retains primitive data types that are not objects. In a 100% OOP language like Smalltalk, everything — including numbers and booleans — is an object with methods and state. Java deliberately includes 8 primitive types (byte, short, int, long, float, double, char, boolean) for performance reasons. Primitives are stored directly on the stack or in memory fields without object overhead (no object header, no method dispatch, no inheritance hierarchy), making arithmetic and array operations significantly faster and more memory-efficient.\n\nAdditionally, static members (variables and methods) belong to the class itself rather than to any instance, meaning they can be accessed without creating an object. This breaks the OOP principle that all behavior should be invoked through objects. For example, Math.sqrt(25) or System.out.println() work without instantiating Math or System.\n\nJava also does not support multiple class inheritance (a class can extend only one parent class), though it allows implementing multiple interfaces. Some consider this a deviation from pure OOP where multiple inheritance might be expected.\n\nJava bridges the gap partially through wrapper classes (Integer, Double, Boolean, etc.) and autoboxing/unboxing, which automatically convert between primitives and their object counterparts. However, the underlying primitives remain non-objects. The trade-off is intentional: Java chose pragmatic performance over theoretical purity, and the wrapper classes provide object-based alternatives when OOP semantics are needed (e.g., in Collections).", code:`int x = 10;        // NOT an object\nInteger xObj = 10;  // IS an object (wrapper)\nstatic int count;   // no object needed`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Primitives (int, char, byte, etc.) are NOT objects. Static members belong to class, not instances. No multiple class inheritance. Wrapper classes bridge the gap but primitives remain for performance." },
      { id:"b6", question:"What are the primitive data types in Java?", answer:"Java has exactly 8 primitive data types, divided into four categories. Their sizes are fixed and platform-independent (unlike C/C++), which is key to Java's architecture neutrality.\n\nNumeric Integer Types:\n- byte: 1 byte (8 bits), range -128 to 127. Used for saving memory in large arrays and for file I/O/stream processing where data is byte-oriented.\n- short: 2 bytes (16 bits), range -32,768 to 32,767. Rarely used, mainly for memory-constrained situations.\n- int: 4 bytes (32 bits), range -2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647. The default and most commonly used integer type for arithmetic, loop counters, and array indices.\n- long: 8 bytes (64 bits), range ±9.2 quintillion. Used when int range is insufficient (timestamps, large calculations). Literal suffix: L (e.g., 999999L).\n\nNumeric Floating-Point Types:\n- float: 4 bytes (32 bits), IEEE 754 single-precision, ~6-7 significant decimal digits. Literal suffix: f (e.g., 3.14f). Used when memory savings matter more than precision.\n- double: 8 bytes (64 bits), IEEE 754 double-precision, ~15 significant decimal digits. The default floating-point type. Used for most decimal calculations.\n\nOther Types:\n- char: 2 bytes (16 bits), stores Unicode characters (0 to 65,535). Uses single quotes ('A'). Java uses UTF-16 encoding internally.\n- boolean: size is JVM-dependent (virtually 1 bit logically), values: true or false. Used for conditional logic. Cannot be converted to/from numeric types.\n\nDefault values for fields: 0 (numeric), '\\u0000' (char), false (boolean). Local variables have NO default and must be initialized before use — the compiler enforces this. Each primitive has a corresponding wrapper class in java.lang for use in object contexts.", code:`byte b=127; short s=32767; int i=2147483647;\nlong l=999999L; float f=3.14f; double d=3.14;\nchar c='A'; boolean bool=true;`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Sizes are fixed across platforms (architecture neutral). Default values apply to fields only; locals must be initialized. Each primitive has a corresponding wrapper class." },
      { id:"b7", question:"What is type casting? Widening vs narrowing?", answer:"Type casting is the process of converting a value from one data type to another. Java supports two kinds of type casting: implicit (widening) and explicit (narrowing).\n\nWidening (Automatic/Implicit Casting): Converting a smaller primitive type to a larger primitive type. This happens automatically because there is no risk of data loss — the larger type can always accommodate all values of the smaller type. The widening conversion path is: byte → short → int → long → float → double. For example, assigning an int to a long is safe because long has a wider range. The compiler inserts the conversion without requiring any explicit syntax. Even int→float and long→double are considered widening, though some precision may be lost for very large values (the magnitude is preserved but exact digits may not be).\n\nNarrowing (Explicit Casting): Converting a larger primitive type to a smaller one. This is NOT automatic because data can be lost — the smaller type cannot represent all values of the larger type. You must explicitly write the cast operator (targetType) to tell the compiler you accept the risk. The narrowing path is the reverse: double → float → long → int → short → byte. When narrowing, the fractional part is truncated (not rounded) for floating-point to integer conversions, and the lower bits are kept while upper bits are discarded for integer-to-integer conversions. For example, (int)166.78 gives 166 (fractional part dropped), and (byte)300 gives 44 (300 - 256 = 44, keeps only the lowest 8 bits).\n\nImportant rules: Boolean cannot be cast to/from any other type. Object reference casting also exists (parent→child requires explicit cast), but that operates on the inheritance hierarchy, not on numeric values.", code:`// Widening (auto)\nint i=100; long l=i; double d=l;\n// Narrowing (explicit)\ndouble d=166.78; int i=(int)d; // 166`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Widening: byte→short→int→long→float→double. No data loss. Narrowing: reverse direction, explicit cast required, fractional part truncated." },
      { id:"b8", question:"What is autoboxing and unboxing?", answer:"Autoboxing and unboxing are automatic conversions between primitive types and their corresponding wrapper classes, introduced in Java 5. They bridge the gap between Java's primitive-centric performance and the object-oriented Collections framework.\n\nAutoboxing: The automatic conversion of a primitive value to its corresponding wrapper object. This occurs when: (1) assigning a primitive to a wrapper type variable (Integer obj = 42;), (2) passing a primitive where a wrapper is expected (list.add(10); where List<Integer>), (3) returning a primitive from a method declared to return a wrapper. The compiler automatically inserts a call to the wrapper's valueOf() method. For Integer, valueOf() uses a cache for values between -128 and 127, returning the same object for cached values.\n\nUnboxing: The automatic conversion of a wrapper object to its corresponding primitive value. This occurs when: (1) assigning a wrapper to a primitive variable (int prim = obj;), (2) performing arithmetic on a wrapper (Integer a=5, b=3; int sum=a+b; — both are unboxed before addition), (3) passing a wrapper where a primitive is expected (System.out.println(obj); calls intValue()). The compiler inserts a call to the wrapper's xxxValue() method (intValue(), doubleValue(), etc.).\n\nCritical pitfalls: (1) Unboxing a null wrapper throws NullPointerException — Integer obj=null; int x=obj; // NPE! (2) The Integer cache (-128 to 127) means Integer a=127, b=127; a==b is true (same cached object), but Integer c=128, d=128; c==d is false (different objects). Always use .equals() for wrapper comparison. (3) Autoboxing/unboxing creates hidden objects that can impact performance in tight loops — prefer primitives when objects aren't needed.", code:`Integer obj = 42;    // autoboxing: int→Integer\nint prim = obj;      // unboxing: Integer→int\nList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();\nlist.add(10);        // autoboxing\nint v = list.get(0); // unboxing`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Autoboxing happens when adding primitives to Collections. Unboxing happens during arithmetic/assignment. Caution: unboxing null→NPE. Integer caches -128 to 127." },
      { id:"b9", question:"Difference between == and .equals()?", answer:"The == operator and .equals() method serve fundamentally different purposes for object comparison in Java.\n\n== Operator: For primitive types, == compares the actual values (5==5 is true). For object reference types, == compares the memory addresses (references) — it checks whether two references point to the exact same object in the heap, NOT whether the objects have equivalent content. For example, new String('Hi')==new String('Hi') is false because two separate String objects exist at different memory locations, even though their content is identical. However, String s3='Hi', s4='Hi'; s3==s4 is true because both refer to the same String Pool object.\n\n.equals() Method: Defined in Object class as a reference comparison (same as ==), but most classes override it to compare logical content/state. String overrides .equals() to compare character-by-character, so new String('Hi').equals(new String('Hi')) is true. Integer, Double, and other wrappers also override .equals() for value comparison. If you create your own class and don't override .equals(), it inherits Object's implementation which uses == (reference comparison).\n\nThe contract of .equals() (from Object Javadoc) requires: reflexive (x.equals(x) is true), symmetric (x.equals(y) ↔ y.equals(x)), transitive (x.equals(y) and y.equals(z) → x.equals(z)), consistent (multiple calls return same result), and x.equals(null) is false. Always override hashCode() when you override .equals() — equal objects must have equal hash codes.\n\nCommon pitfalls: (1) Using == for String comparison — always use .equals(). (2) Integer cache trap: Integer a=127, b=127; a==b is true (cached), but Integer c=128, d=128; c==d is false (not cached). (3) Not overriding .equals() in custom classes — defaults to reference comparison.", code:`String s1=new String("Hi"), s2=new String("Hi");\ns1==s2;      // false (different objects)\ns1.equals(s2); // true (same content)\nString s3="Hi", s4="Hi";\ns3==s4;      // true (same pool ref)`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Use == for primitives and null checks. Use .equals() for object content comparison. String and wrappers override .equals(). Integer caches -128 to 127 so == may work by coincidence." },
      { id:"b10", question:"What is the main() method? Why public static void?", answer:"The main() method is the designated entry point for any standalone Java application. When you run 'java MyApp', the JVM loads the class and invokes its main() method to begin execution. The signature must be: public static void main(String[] args). Each keyword has a specific reason:\n\npublic: The JVM is external to your application's package and class hierarchy. It needs to call main() from outside the class, so the method must be public (accessible from anywhere). If main() were private, protected, or package-private, the JVM could not invoke it.\n\nstatic: The JVM must call main() before any objects are created. Since static methods belong to the class rather than instances, the JVM can invoke main() directly using the class name (MyApp.main()) without needing to instantiate the class first. Without static, the JVM would need to create an object first, but which constructor should it use? There's no way for the JVM to know.\n\nvoid: The main() method does not return a value to the JVM. When main() completes, the application terminates (unless non-daemon threads are still running). The JVM doesn't expect or handle a return value from main(). To signal exit status, use System.exit(int) where 0=success, non-zero=error.\n\nmain: The method name is fixed by convention and JVM specification. The JVM specifically looks for a method named 'main' with the exact signature.\n\nString[] args: Command-line arguments passed when the program starts. For 'java MyApp file.txt 42', args[0]='file.txt', args[1]='42'. All arguments are Strings — numeric arguments must be parsed manually. The array can be empty but never null. Java 5+ also accepts: main(String... args) (varargs form, functionally identical).\n\nValid overloads: You can have multiple main() methods with different signatures (overloading), but only the exact signature above is the JVM entry point. Each class can have a main() — the one called depends on which class you specify to the java command.", code:`public static void main(String[] args) {\n    System.out.println("Entry point");\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"public: JVM accesses from outside. static: JVM calls before objects exist. void: no return value. main: fixed name. String[] args: command-line arguments. Valid: main(String... args) too." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "oops",
    title: "OOP Concepts",
    icon: "🧱",
    questions: [
      { id:"o1", question:"What are the four pillars of OOP?", answer:"Object-Oriented Programming is built on four fundamental pillars that work together to create modular, maintainable, and scalable software.\n\n1. Encapsulation: The bundling of data (attributes) and methods (behaviors) that operate on that data into a single unit (class), while restricting direct access to the internal state. Encapsulation is achieved through access modifiers — fields are declared private and accessed through public getter/setter methods. This provides data hiding (internal representation is hidden), controlled access (validation logic in setters), and flexibility to change internal implementation without breaking external code. Example: A BankAccount class keeps balance private and provides a deposit() method that validates the amount before modifying balance.\n\n2. Inheritance: The mechanism by which a child class (subclass) acquires the properties and behaviors of a parent class (superclass). Inheritance establishes an 'is-a' relationship (Dog is-a Animal) and promotes code reuse — common functionality is defined once in the parent and inherited by all children. The child class can add new fields/methods or override parent methods to provide specialized behavior. Java supports single class inheritance (extends one class) but multiple interface implementation (implements multiple interfaces).\n\n3. Polymorphism: The ability of an object to take many forms. There are two types: Compile-time polymorphism (method overloading — same method name, different parameters in the same class) and Runtime polymorphism (method overriding — subclass provides its own implementation of a parent method, and the JVM determines which version to call based on the actual object type at runtime). Polymorphism enables writing code that works with parent type references but executes child-specific behavior: Shape s = new Circle(); s.area(); calls Circle's area().\n\n4. Abstraction: The process of hiding complex implementation details and showing only essential features to the user. Abstraction focuses on 'what' an object does rather than 'how' it does it. In Java, abstraction is achieved through abstract classes (can have both abstract and concrete methods) and interfaces (pure abstraction before Java 8, now with default/static methods). Example: You drive a car using steering and pedals (abstracted interface) without knowing the internal engine mechanics.", code:`// Encapsulation: private fields + public methods\nclass BankAccount {\n    private double balance;\n    public void deposit(double a) { if(a>0) balance+=a; }\n}\n// Inheritance: child extends parent\nclass Dog extends Animal { }\n// Polymorphism: same interface, different behavior\nclass Circle extends Shape { double area() { return Math.PI*r*r; } }\n// Abstraction: hide complexity\nabstract class Vehicle { abstract void start(); }`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Encapsulation: bundle data+methods, restrict access. Inheritance: child acquires parent properties. Polymorphism: many forms (overloading+overriding). Abstraction: show what, hide how." },
      { id:"o2", question:"Method overloading vs overriding?", answer:"Method Overloading and Method Overriding are two forms of polymorphism in Java, but they differ fundamentally in how and when they are resolved.\n\nMethod Overloading (Compile-Time Polymorphism / Static Binding): Multiple methods in the SAME class share the same name but have different parameter lists (different number, types, or order of parameters). The compiler determines which overloaded method to call based on the method signature at compile time — this is called static binding or early binding. Return type alone cannot distinguish overloaded methods (changing only return type causes compile error). Overloading can also happen across parent-child classes (the child inherits parent methods and adds its own overloaded versions). Overloaded methods can have different access modifiers and can throw different checked exceptions. Example: int add(int a, int b) and double add(double a, double b) are overloaded.\n\nMethod Overriding (Runtime Polymorphism / Dynamic Binding): A subclass provides its own specific implementation of a method that is already defined in its parent class. The method signature (name, parameters, return type) must be exactly the same (covariant return types allowed since Java 5). The JVM determines which overridden method to execute based on the actual object type at runtime — this is dynamic binding or late binding. Rules: (1) Access modifier cannot be more restrictive (can be wider: protected→public), (2) Cannot override final, static, or private methods, (3) Cannot throw broader checked exceptions, (4) Must use @Override annotation for compiler verification, (5) Only applicable in parent-child relationship. Example: Dog extends Animal and overrides sound() to print 'Bark' instead of Animal's generic sound.\n\nKey difference: Overloading is about 'same name, different parameters' resolved at compile time. Overriding is about 'same signature, different implementation' resolved at runtime.", code:`// Overloading\nint add(int a, int b) { return a+b; }\ndouble add(double a, double b) { return a+b; }\n// Overriding\nclass Dog extends Animal {\n    @Override void sound() { System.out.println("Bark"); }\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Overloading=compile-time, same class, params must differ. Overriding=runtime, parent-child, same signature. Cannot override static/final methods. @Override annotation recommended." },
      { id:"o3", question:"What is encapsulation? How achieved?", answer:"Encapsulation is the OOP principle of bundling data (fields) and the methods that operate on that data into a single unit (class), while restricting direct access to the internal representation. The core idea is data hiding — the internal state of an object should not be directly accessible or modifiable from outside the object. Instead, access is controlled through well-defined public methods (getters and setters) that enforce validation rules and maintain invariants.\n\nHow Encapsulation is Achieved in Java:\n1. Declare fields as private — this prevents external code from directly reading or modifying the field. Other classes cannot access private members.\n2. Provide public getter methods — controlled read access. A getter returns the field value but doesn't expose the internal representation. For example, a Date field could be returned as a formatted String, hiding the actual Date object.\n3. Provide public setter methods — controlled write access with validation. A setter can reject invalid values before modifying the field. For example, setAge(-5) can be rejected while setAge(25) is accepted.\n4. Optional: Create read-only fields by providing only a getter (no setter), or write-only fields by providing only a setter (rare, e.g., password).\n\nBenefits of Encapsulation:\n- Data Protection: Prevents external code from putting the object into an invalid state.\n- Flexibility: You can change the internal implementation (e.g., switch from int age to LocalDate birthDate) without breaking any code that uses the public methods.\n- Maintainability: Validation logic is centralized in one place (the setter), not scattered across all callers.\n- Debugging: You can add logging or breakpoints in setters to track when and how state changes.\n\nEncapsulation is often considered the most fundamental OOP principle because it forms the foundation upon which the other pillars rely — you cannot have proper inheritance or polymorphism without well-encapsulated classes.", code:`class Employee {\n    private int age;\n    public void setAge(int age) {\n        if(age>0 && age<150) this.age=age;\n    }\n    public int getAge() { return age; }\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Private fields prevent direct access. Public setters with validation control writes. Getters control reads. Can make read-only (no setter) or write-only (no getter)." },
      { id:"o4", question:"What is inheritance? Types in Java?", answer:"Inheritance is the OOP mechanism that allows a child class (subclass/derived class) to acquire the properties (fields) and behaviors (methods) of a parent class (superclass/base class). It establishes an 'is-a' relationship — a Dog is-a Animal, a Car is-a Vehicle. The child class inherits all non-private members of the parent and can add new members or override inherited methods to provide specialized behavior. Inheritance promotes code reuse (common logic in parent, specialized in children) and establishes hierarchical relationships between classes.\n\nIn Java, inheritance is implemented using the 'extends' keyword for classes and 'implements' keyword for interfaces. Java supports the following types of inheritance:\n\n1. Single Inheritance: One child extends one parent. class Dog extends Animal { } — simplest form.\n2. Multilevel Inheritance: A chain of inheritance. class Vehicle { } → class Car extends Vehicle { } → class ElectricCar extends Car { } — each level adds specialization.\n3. Hierarchical Inheritance: Multiple children extend one parent. class Animal { } → class Dog extends Animal { }, class Cat extends Animal { } — siblings share the same parent.\n4. Multiple Inheritance: One child inherits from multiple parents. Java does NOT support multiple class inheritance (a class can extend only ONE class) to avoid the Diamond Problem — if two parent classes have the same method, which one does the child inherit? However, Java supports multiple interface implementation: class Duck implements Flyable, Swimmable { }.\n5. Hybrid Inheritance: Combination of above types. Not directly supported in Java for classes but achievable through interfaces.\n\nThe Diamond Problem: When class D extends both B and C, and both B and C override the same method from A, which version does D inherit? Java prevents this by disallowing multiple class inheritance. For interface default methods (Java 8+), the class must explicitly override and choose: class C implements A, B { public void show() { A.super.show(); } }.\n\nImportant rules: (1) Object class is the root of all classes, (2) Constructors are NOT inherited, (3) Private members are NOT inherited (but exist in child), (4) Final classes cannot be extended.", code:`class Dog extends Animal { }  // single\nclass ElectricCar extends Car { } // multilevel\ninterface Flyable { void fly(); }\ninterface Swimmable { void swim(); }\nclass Duck implements Flyable, Swimmable { } // multiple`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"No multiple class inheritance (Diamond Problem). extends=class, implements=interface. Single, multilevel, hierarchical, multiple (interfaces), hybrid." },
      { id:"o5", question:"Abstract class vs Interface?", answer:"Abstract classes and interfaces are both mechanisms for achieving abstraction in Java, but they serve different purposes and have distinct characteristics.\n\nAbstract Class: A class declared with the 'abstract' keyword that cannot be instantiated directly. It can contain: abstract methods (no body, must be overridden by subclasses), concrete methods (with implementation), constructors, instance variables (any access modifier), static methods, and final methods. Abstract classes are used when you want to share common implementation code among related subclasses while enforcing that certain methods must be overridden. A class can extend only ONE abstract class (single inheritance). Access modifiers on abstract methods can be protected or public. Example: abstract class Animal { abstract void sound(); void breathe() { } // shared implementation; String name; // state }\n\nInterface: A contract that defines what a class MUST do without specifying how. Before Java 8, interfaces could only have abstract methods and constants (public static final). Since Java 8: default methods (with body, provide default implementation), static methods. Since Java 9: private methods and private static methods (for code sharing between default methods). Interfaces cannot have: constructors, instance variables (only public static final constants), instance initialization blocks. A class can implement MULTIPLE interfaces. All interface methods are public by default. Fields are public static final by default. Example: interface Drawable { void draw(); default void resize() { } }\n\nWhen to use which:\n- Use Abstract Class when: classes share common state (instance variables), you need constructors, you want to provide common implementation code, you need non-public access modifiers, you're building a family of closely related classes (is-a relationship).\n- Use Interface when: you're defining a capability contract (can-do relationship), you need multiple inheritance of type, you want to define API without implementation, unrelated classes should implement the same behavior.\n\nJava 8+ blurs the line with default methods, but the fundamental difference remains: abstract classes can have state (instance variables), interfaces cannot.", code:`abstract class Animal {\n    abstract void sound();\n    void breathe() { } // concrete\n    String name; // instance var\n}\ninterface Drawable {\n    void draw(); // abstract\n    default void resize() { } // Java 8\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Abstract class: single inheritance, any access modifier, has state. Interface: multiple implementation, public abstract by default, no state (only constants). Use abstract class for shared state; interface for capability contract." },
      { id:"o6", question:"What is polymorphism?", answer:"Polymorphism (Greek: 'many forms') is the ability of an object to take on different forms or behave differently depending on the context. It allows a single interface to represent different underlying implementations, making code more flexible, extensible, and maintainable. Java supports two types of polymorphism:\n\n1. Compile-Time Polymorphism (Static Polymorphism / Static Binding): Resolved at compile time by the compiler based on the method signature. The primary form is method overloading — multiple methods with the same name but different parameter lists in the same class. The compiler determines which method to call by matching the argument types at the call site. This is also called early binding because the method call is bound to the method body before the program runs. Compile-time polymorphism is faster (no runtime dispatch overhead) but less flexible — the decision is fixed at compile time. Example: void show(int a) and void show(String a) — the compiler picks the right one based on argument type.\n\n2. Runtime Polymorphism (Dynamic Polymorphism / Dynamic Binding): Resolved at runtime by the JVM based on the actual object type (not the reference type). The primary form is method overriding — a subclass provides its own implementation of a method defined in the parent class. When a parent type reference points to a child object (upcasting: Shape s = new Circle();), the compiler allows the call (because Shape has area()), but at runtime, the JVM looks at the actual object type (Circle) and calls Circle's version of area(). This is called late binding or dynamic dispatch — the method call is bound to the implementation at runtime. Runtime polymorphism enables writing generic code that works with parent types while automatically executing child-specific behavior.\n\nKey concepts for runtime polymorphism: Upcasting (parent ref = child object) is always safe and automatic. Downcasting (child ref = parent object) requires explicit cast and is risky (ClassCastException). The instanceof operator checks actual type before downcasting. Only overridden instance methods show polymorphic behavior — instance variables, static methods, and private methods do NOT (they use reference type, not object type).", code:`// Compile-time: overloading\nvoid show(int a) { }\nvoid show(String a) { }\n// Runtime: overriding + parent reference\nShape s = new Circle();\ns.area(); // Circle's version at runtime`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Compile-time=static binding, method overloading, faster. Runtime=dynamic binding, method overriding, parent ref=child object, JVM decides at runtime. More flexible." },
      { id:"o7", question:"What is the 'this' keyword?", answer:"The 'this' keyword in Java is a reference variable that refers to the current object — the instance of the class on which a method or constructor is being called. The JVM assigns 'this' implicitly every time an instance method or constructor is invoked. It has several important uses:\n\n1. Distinguishing instance variables from method parameters: When a method parameter has the same name as an instance variable (shadowing), 'this' disambiguates. Example: this.name = name; — this.name refers to the instance variable, name refers to the parameter. This is the most common use of 'this'.\n\n2. Constructor chaining (this() call): Calling one constructor from another constructor in the same class using this(args). This avoids duplicating initialization code across multiple constructors. The this() call MUST be the first statement in the constructor. Example: Student() { this('Unknown'); } calls the parameterized constructor with a default value.\n\n3. Passing the current object as an argument: When you need to pass the current object to another method. Example: validator.validate(this); — passes the current instance to the validator.\n\n4. Returning the current object: return this; enables method chaining (fluent API pattern). Example: Student setName(String n) { this.name=n; return this; } allows: student.setName('Alice').setAge(25);\n\n5. Referring to the current object's instance variables/methods explicitly: Though not required when there's no shadowing, it can improve clarity.\n\nImportant restrictions: (1) this() must be the first statement in a constructor — you cannot have any code before it. (2) 'this' cannot be used in static context (static methods, static blocks, static initializer) because static members belong to the class, not to any instance. (3) Recursive constructor calls using this() are not allowed (constructor A calls constructor B which calls constructor A) — the compiler detects this as a cycle.", code:`Student(String name) { this.name=name; } // distinguish\nStudent() { this("Unknown"); } // constructor chaining\nStudent setName(String n) { this.name=n; return this; } // chaining`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"this() must be first statement in constructor. Cannot use in static context. return this enables fluent API/method chaining." },
      { id:"o8", question:"What is the 'super' keyword?", answer:"The 'super' keyword in Java is a reference variable that refers to the immediate parent class object. It is used in subclass contexts to access parent class members that have been hidden or overridden. Like 'this', 'super' is implicitly available in instance methods and constructors. Its uses include:\n\n1. Calling the parent class constructor (super()): When a child class needs to explicitly invoke a specific parent constructor. If the parent class has no default (no-arg) constructor, the child MUST call super(args) as the first statement in its constructor to pass the required arguments. Even when the parent has a default constructor, the compiler inserts super() automatically as the first line if you don't write it. super() must always be the first statement in the constructor — no code can precede it.\n\n2. Accessing parent class variables hidden by subclass variables: When a subclass declares a variable with the same name as a parent variable (variable shadowing), super.variableName accesses the parent's version. Example: super.name refers to the parent's name field when the child also has a name field.\n\n3. Calling parent class methods that have been overridden: When a subclass overrides a parent method, super.methodName() explicitly calls the parent's version. This is commonly used when the child wants to extend (not replace) the parent's behavior: @Override void sound() { super.sound(); System.out.println('Bark'); } — first calls parent's sound(), then adds child-specific behavior.\n\nImportant rules: (1) super() must be the first statement in the constructor, (2) super refers to the IMMEDIATE parent only (not grandparent — you cannot chain super.super), (3) Cannot use super in static context — it requires an instance, (4) If parent has no default constructor and child doesn't explicitly call super(args), the compiler raises an error, (5) In constructor chaining, either this() or super() can be the first statement, but not both — if you use this() to chain to another constructor, that constructor must eventually call super().", code:`Dog() { super("Default"); } // parent constructor\nSystem.out.println(super.name); // parent variable\nsuper.sound(); // parent method in overriding`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"super() must be first statement. If parent has no default constructor, child MUST call super(args). Refers to immediate parent only. Cannot use in static context." },
      { id:"o9", question:"What are access modifiers?", answer:"Access modifiers in Java are keywords that control the visibility and accessibility of classes, interfaces, methods, constructors, and fields from other classes and packages. They are fundamental to encapsulation. Java provides four access levels, from most restrictive to least:\n\n1. private: Accessible ONLY within the same class. Not visible to any other class, including subclasses and classes in the same package. Used for internal implementation details that should be completely hidden. All fields should typically be private (encapsulation best practice). Private members are NOT inherited by subclasses (though they exist in the subclass object, they cannot be accessed directly).\n\n2. default (package-private / no modifier): When no access modifier is specified, the member is accessible to all classes within the SAME package only. Not accessible to classes in other packages, even subclasses. This is the default for classes (top-level classes can only be public or default). Useful for package-level utility methods that should not be exposed outside the package.\n\n3. protected: Accessible within the same package AND to subclasses in OTHER packages. This is strictly more permissive than default — it adds cross-package subclass access. Used for members that subclasses need to access or override but that should remain hidden from unrelated classes. Protected members ARE inherited by subclasses.\n\n4. public: Accessible from EVERYWHERE — any class in any package can access the member. Used for the API surface of a class: public methods that external code should call, public constants, and public classes. Should be used sparingly for fields (breaks encapsulation).\n\nAccessibility Summary Table:\n| Modifier   | Same Class | Same Package | Subclass (Diff Pkg) | World |\n| private    |    Yes     |     No       |       No            |  No   |\n| default    |    Yes     |     Yes      |       No            |  No   |\n| protected  |    Yes     |     Yes      |       Yes           |  No   |\n| public     |    Yes     |     Yes      |       Yes           |  Yes  |\n\nBest practices: Fields should be private. Provide public getters/setters. Use protected for methods that subclasses should override. Use default for package-internal helpers. Minimize public surface area.", code:`private int a;    // class only\nint b;            // package (default)\nprotected int c;  // package + subclasses\npublic int d;     // everywhere`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Most→least restrictive: private→default→protected→public. Best practice: fields private, public getters/setters, protected for subclass methods. Top-level classes: public or default only." },
      { id:"o10", question:"What is the 'static' keyword?", answer:"The 'static' keyword in Java indicates that a member (variable, method, block, or nested class) belongs to the class itself rather than to any specific instance of the class. Static members are shared across ALL instances of the class — there is only ONE copy of a static variable regardless of how many objects are created. Static members can be accessed without creating an object, using the class name: ClassName.staticMember.\n\nStatic Variables (Class Variables): Declared with static keyword. Shared by all instances — changing it from one object affects all objects. Memory is allocated once when the class is loaded. Used for: counters (tracking number of instances), constants (static final, e.g., Math.PI), configuration values shared across instances. Example: static int count=0; in a constructor increments count++ — all instances share the same count.\n\nStatic Methods (Class Methods): Declared with static keyword. Can be called without an object: ClassName.method(). Cannot access instance variables or instance methods directly (no 'this' reference) because they don't belong to any instance. Can access other static members directly. Used for: utility methods (Math.sqrt(), Collections.sort()), factory methods, main() method. Example: static int getCount() { return count; } — accesses static variable without needing an instance.\n\nStatic Blocks: Initialization blocks that run ONCE when the class is loaded by the ClassLoader, before any object is created or static method is called. Used for complex static initialization that can't be done in a single line. Multiple static blocks execute in order of appearance. Example: static { System.loadLibrary('native'); } — loads a native library when the class loads.\n\nStatic Nested Classes: A class defined within another class with the static keyword. Unlike inner classes, static nested classes do not have a reference to the outer class instance — they behave like top-level classes nested inside another class for packaging convenience. Can access outer class's static members (including private). Example: class Outer { static class Nested { } } — new Outer.Nested() without creating Outer instance.\n\nKey restrictions: (1) Cannot use 'this' or 'super' in static context, (2) Cannot access instance members directly from static methods, (3) Cannot override static methods (only hiding — based on reference type), (4) Cannot make top-level class static (only nested classes).", code:`class Counter {\n    static int count=0; // shared\n    int id; // unique per instance\n    Counter() { count++; id=count; }\n    static int getCount() { return count; }\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Static: variable (shared), method (no this, no instance access), block (runs once on class load), nested class (no outer instance). Use for utility methods, constants, counters, factory methods." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "strings",
    title: "String Handling",
    icon: "📝",
    questions: [
      { id:"s1", question:"What is the String Pool?", answer:"The String Pool (also called String Constant Pool or Intern Pool) is a special memory area within the Java Heap where String literals are stored and reused. When you create a String using a literal (String s = \"Hello\"), the JVM checks the pool first — if \"Hello\" already exists, it returns a reference to the existing pooled String; if not, it creates a new String object in the pool and returns its reference. This mechanism saves memory by ensuring that identical String literals share the same object rather than creating duplicates.\n\nHow it works: The pool is a HashMap-like structure maintained by the JVM. At class load time, all String literals in the class are added to the pool. When String s1=\"Hello\" and String s2=\"Hello\" are encountered, both s1 and s2 point to the SAME object in the pool, so s1==s2 is true (reference equality). However, String s3=new String(\"Hello\") creates a NEW object on the heap (outside the pool), even though \"Hello\" already exists in the pool. So s1==s3 is false — different memory locations. To add a heap String to the pool, call intern(): s1==s3.intern() is true because intern() returns the pooled version.\n\nKey rules: (1) String literals are automatically placed in the pool. (2) Compile-time constant concatenation (\"Hel\"+\"lo\") results in a pooled String. (3) Runtime concatenation (s1+s2) creates a heap object, NOT pooled. (4) The intern() method manually adds a String to the pool if not already present. (5) The pool is part of the PermGen space before Java 7, and moved to the main heap in Java 7+ to avoid OutOfMemoryError: PermGen space. (6) The pool makes String immutability essential — if Strings were mutable, one reference changing a pooled String would corrupt all other references to it.", code:`String s1="Hello"; String s2="Hello";\ns1==s2; // true (same pool ref)\nString s3=new String("Hello");\ns1==s3; // false (heap, not pool)\ns1==s3.intern(); // true (added to pool)`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Literals auto-pooled. new String() creates heap object. intern() adds to pool. Compile-time concat→pool; runtime concat→heap. Immutability makes pool safe." },
      { id:"s2", question:"Why is String immutable?", answer:"String immutability is one of the most fundamental design decisions in Java. Once a String object is created, its value cannot be changed — any operation that appears to modify a String actually creates a new String object. This is enforced at the language level by: (1) the String class is declared final (cannot be subclassed), (2) the internal character array (byte[] in Java 9+, char[] in Java 8) is private and final, (3) no methods in String modify the internal array — all methods like replace, substring, concat, toUpperCase return NEW String objects.\n\nReasons for immutability:\n1. String Pool Safety: The String Pool relies on immutability. Multiple reference variables can safely point to the same String object in the pool because no reference can change the object's value. If Strings were mutable, changing a String through one reference would corrupt all other references pointing to the same pooled object.\n2. Security: Strings are used extensively in Java's security infrastructure — class names, file paths, network URLs, database connections, and class loading all use Strings. If Strings were mutable, a malicious program could change a class name after the security check but before class loading, bypassing security. Immutability ensures that once verified, a String value cannot be tampered with.\n3. Thread Safety (Concurrency): Immutable objects are inherently thread-safe — they can be shared between threads without synchronization because their state never changes. This makes Strings safe to use in multi-threaded environments without any locking overhead.\n4. HashCode Caching: Since a String's value never changes, its hash code can be computed once and cached. The String class caches the hash code in a field, and all subsequent calls to hashCode() return the cached value. This makes Strings extremely efficient as HashMap keys — the hash is computed only once per String.\n5. Class Loading: The JVM uses Strings to represent class and method names during class loading. Immutability ensures that the correct class is always loaded and that class names cannot be changed between resolution and loading.\n6. Reliability: Immutability eliminates an entire category of bugs where one part of code unexpectedly modifies a String that another part depends on.", code:`String s1="Hello";\nString s2=s1.concat(" World"); // NEW object\nSystem.out.println(s1); // "Hello" unchanged`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Pool safety: shared refs can't corrupt each other. Security: class names, URLs can't be tampered. Thread-safe: no sync needed. Hashcode cached: HashMap fast. Enforced by: final class, private final char[]/byte[], no mutating methods." },
      { id:"s3", question:"String vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer?", answer:"These three classes represent text in Java with different mutability and thread-safety characteristics.\n\nString: Immutable sequence of characters. Every operation that appears to modify a String (concat, replace, substring, etc.) creates a brand new String object, leaving the original unchanged. This makes String operations expensive when repeated concatenation is involved — String s=\"a\"; s+=\"b\"; s+=\"c\"; creates 3 separate objects (\"a\", \"ab\", \"abc\"), with the intermediate objects becoming garbage. Use String when the text won't change (constants, configuration values, keys) or when you need immutability for safety (HashMap keys, multi-threaded sharing).\n\nStringBuilder: Mutable sequence of characters, introduced in Java 5. NOT thread-safe (no synchronization). Modifications (append, insert, delete, replace) happen in-place on the same object without creating new objects. This makes StringBuilder much faster than String for building or modifying text. The internal buffer grows automatically (default capacity 16, grows by (old*2)+2) to accommodate additions. Use StringBuilder for: building strings in loops, concatenating many strings, formatting output, single-threaded scenarios. Example: StringBuilder sb=new StringBuilder(); for(int i=0;i<1000;i++) sb.append(i); creates ONE object, not 1000.\n\nStringBuffer: Mutable sequence of characters, present since Java 1.0. Thread-safe — all public methods are synchronized, meaning only one thread can access a StringBuffer at a time. This synchronization provides safety in multi-threaded environments but adds performance overhead (every method call acquires/releases a lock). Use StringBuffer when: multiple threads need to modify the same text concurrently (rare in practice). In most real-world scenarios, thread-local StringBuilders are preferred over shared StringBuffers.\n\nPerformance comparison: StringBuilder > StringBuffer >> String (for modifications). String concatenation using + in a single statement is optimized by the compiler to use StringBuilder automatically, but + in loops creates a new StringBuilder per iteration — use explicit StringBuilder in loops.", code:`StringBuilder sb=new StringBuilder("Hi");\nsb.append(" World"); // modifies same object\nStringBuffer sbuf=new StringBuffer("Hi");\nsbuf.append(" World"); // synchronized methods`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"String=slowest for concatenation (new objects). StringBuilder=fastest, single-thread. StringBuffer=medium, multi-thread. Use String for constants, StringBuilder for building, StringBuffer for multi-thread (rare)." },
      { id:"s4", question:"Important String methods?", answer:"Java's String class provides over 60 methods for text manipulation. They can be organized into functional categories:\n\nAccess Methods: length() returns character count, charAt(index) returns the character at a specific position (0-based), isEmpty() checks if length is 0, isBlank() (Java 11) checks if string is empty or contains only whitespace.\n\nExtraction Methods: substring(begin) returns from begin to end, substring(begin, end) returns from begin to end-1 (end is EXCLUSIVE — common pitfall), subSequence(begin, end) returns CharSequence.\n\nComparison Methods: equals(Object) compares content exactly (case-sensitive), equalsIgnoreCase(String) compares ignoring case, compareTo(String) returns negative/zero/positive for lexicographic ordering, compareToIgnoreCase(String) same but case-insensitive, contentEquals(CharSequence) compares with any CharSequence (StringBuffer, StringBuilder).\n\nSearch Methods: indexOf(char/String) returns first occurrence index or -1, lastIndexOf(char/String) returns last occurrence, contains(CharSequence) returns true if substring exists, startsWith(String)/endsWith(String) check prefix/suffix.\n\nModification Methods (all return NEW String): replace(char, char) replaces all occurrences of a character, replaceAll(String regex, String replacement) regex-based replacement, replaceFirst(String regex, String replacement) first match only, trim() removes leading/trailing whitespace (ASCII only), strip() (Java 11) Unicode-aware whitespace removal, stripLeading()/stripTrailing() (Java 11), toUpperCase()/toLowerCase() case conversion.\n\nSplit/Join Methods: split(String regex) splits into String array, String.join(CharSequence delimiter, CharSequence... elements) static method for joining, String.join(CharSequence delimiter, Iterable) joins collections.\n\nConversion Methods: toCharArray() converts to char array, getBytes() converts to byte array using default charset, getBytes(Charset) converts using specified charset, valueOf(primitive/Object) static method to convert any type to String, formatted(String format, Object... args) (Java 15) String.format equivalent.\n\nCommon pitfalls: substring end index is exclusive, replace uses char not CharSequence for single-char version, split regex requires escaping (e.g., split(\"\\\\.\") for literal dot), trim only handles ASCII whitespace (use strip for Unicode).", code:`String s="Hello, World!";\ns.length(); s.charAt(0); s.substring(7);\ns.equals("hi"); s.equalsIgnoreCase("hello, world!");\ns.contains("World"); s.indexOf("World");\ns.replace('o','0'); s.trim();\nString.join("-","a","b"); "a,b".split(",");`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Categories: Access(length,charAt), Extraction(substring), Comparison(equals,compareTo), Search(indexOf,contains), Modification(replace,trim,toUpperCase), Split/Join, Check(isEmpty,isBlank). Pitfall: substring end is exclusive." },
      { id:"s5", question:"equals() vs contentEquals()?", answer:"Both methods compare String content, but they differ in what types they accept and how they perform the comparison.\n\nequals(Object obj): Defined in Object class and overridden in String. It accepts ANY Object as parameter. The String implementation first checks if the argument is instanceof String — if not, it immediately returns false. Then it compares the character arrays element by element. This means equals() can only return true when comparing a String with another String object. It will always return false for StringBuffer, StringBuilder, or any other CharSequence implementation, even if they contain identical characters.\n\ncontentEquals(CharSequence cs): Introduced in Java 5 specifically to compare String content with any CharSequence implementation (String, StringBuilder, StringBuffer, CharBuffer, etc.). It does NOT check instanceof String — instead, it compares character-by-character against any CharSequence. This makes it the correct choice when comparing a String with a StringBuilder or StringBuffer.\n\nWhen to use which: Use equals() when comparing two Strings (most common case). Use contentEquals() when comparing a String with a StringBuilder, StringBuffer, or other CharSequence. Never use == for content comparison — it compares references, not content.\n\nPerformance: equals() is slightly faster when comparing two Strings because it can first check length and then do a bulk comparison. contentEquals() must iterate character-by-character for non-String CharSeqences. However, contentEquals(String) has an optimized path that delegates to equals().", code:`String s="Hello";\nStringBuffer sb=new StringBuffer("Hello");\ns.equals(sb); // false (not a String)\ns.contentEquals(sb); // true (char sequence)`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"equals() checks instanceof String first. contentEquals() accepts any CharSequence, compares char-by-char. Use contentEquals when comparing with StringBuilder/StringBuffer." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "inheritance-polymorphism",
    title: "Inheritance & Polymorphism Deep Dive",
    icon: "🔗",
    questions: [
      { id:"ip1", question:"Can you override a static method?", answer:"No, static methods cannot be overridden in Java. When you define a static method in a subclass with the same signature as a static method in the parent class, it is called 'method hiding' (also known as shadowing), not overriding. The distinction is critical: overriding relies on runtime polymorphism (dynamic dispatch), where the JVM looks at the actual object type to decide which method to call. Static methods, however, use static binding (compile-time resolution) — the compiler determines which method to call based on the reference type, not the object type.\n\nWhen you write Parent p = new Child(); p.show(); — if show() is static, the compiler sees that p is declared as type Parent, so it binds the call to Parent.show() at compile time. The fact that p actually points to a Child object is irrelevant for static methods. This is the opposite of instance method overriding, where p.show() would call Child's version at runtime.\n\nThis behavior is defined in the JLS (Java Language Specification) §8.4.8.2: 'If a static method is declared, it hides all methods with the same signature in superclasses.' The @Override annotation will cause a compile error if applied to a static method — confirming that the compiler does not consider it overriding.\n\nBest practice: Always call static methods using the class name (Parent.show() or Child.show()) rather than through an instance reference. This makes the code unambiguous and prevents confusion about which method is being invoked. IDEs and linters typically warn about calling static methods via instance references.", code:`class Parent { static void show() { System.out.println("P"); } }\nclass Child extends Parent { static void show() { System.out.println("C"); } }\nParent p=new Child(); p.show(); // "P" — ref type decides`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Static methods use static binding (compile-time). No virtual dispatch. Called on class, not instance. Always call static methods via class name for clarity." },
      { id:"ip2", question:"What is covariant return type?", answer:"Covariant return type is a feature introduced in Java 5 that allows an overriding method in a subclass to return a more specific type (a subtype) than the return type declared in the parent class's overridden method. Before Java 5, the overriding method had to return exactly the same type as the parent method, which often forced developers to cast the return value manually.\n\nThe word 'covariant' comes from type theory — it means the return type varies in the same direction as the subclass relationship (as the class becomes more specific, the return type also becomes more specific). The overriding method's return type must be a subtype of the parent method's return type — it cannot be a supertype or an unrelated type.\n\nRules: (1) The return type must be a subtype (for reference types only — primitives must match exactly), (2) The method signature (name and parameter types) must still match exactly, (3) This is true overriding, not overloading — the @Override annotation applies correctly, (4) The covariant return must be a reference type — you cannot change int to short or double to float.\n\nCommon use case: Factory method patterns where each subclass factory returns its own specific type. class AnimalFactory { Animal create() { return new Animal(); } } class DogFactory extends AnimalFactory { @Override Dog create() { return new Dog(); } } — callers of DogFactory.create() get a Dog directly without casting. Clone() methods also benefit: Object clone() in parent can be overridden to return the specific type in each subclass.", code:`class AnimalFactory { Animal create() { return new Animal(); } }\nclass DogFactory extends AnimalFactory {\n    @Override Dog create() { return new Dog(); } // covariant\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Return type must be subtype. Only for reference types. Method signature must still match. True overriding, not overloading." },
      { id:"ip3", question:"Diamond Problem? How does Java handle it?", answer:"The Diamond Problem is a fundamental ambiguity that arises in languages that support multiple inheritance of classes. It occurs when a class D inherits from two classes B and C, and both B and C override the same method from a common parent A. The question is: which version of the method does D inherit — B's or C's? The inheritance diagram forms a diamond shape (A at top, B and C in middle, D at bottom), hence the name.\n\nHow Java handles it for classes: Java completely avoids the Diamond Problem by disallowing multiple class inheritance. A Java class can extend exactly ONE parent class (single inheritance). This eliminates the ambiguity entirely — there is always exactly one inheritance path for any method. The trade-off is that you cannot reuse code from multiple class hierarchies, but Java provides interfaces as an alternative for sharing behavior contracts.\n\nHow Java handles it for interfaces (Java 8+): With the introduction of default methods in interfaces, a form of the Diamond Problem can arise. If a class implements two interfaces that both provide a default method with the same signature, the compiler forces the class to explicitly resolve the conflict by overriding the method. Inside the overriding method, you can choose which interface's default implementation to call using InterfaceName.super.methodName(). Example: class C implements A, B { public void show() { A.super.show(); } } explicitly chooses A's implementation.\n\nResolution rules (in order of priority): (1) Class method wins over interface default method, (2) More specific interface wins over less specific (sub-interface beats super-interface), (3) If neither is more specific, the class MUST override and disambiguate explicitly. This design ensures there is never ambiguity — the compiler will always flag the conflict and require explicit resolution.", code:`interface A { default void show() { System.out.println("A"); } }\ninterface B { default void show() { System.out.println("B"); } }\nclass C implements A, B {\n    public void show() { A.super.show(); } // resolve explicitly\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"No multiple class inheritance = no Diamond Problem. For conflicting default methods, class MUST override. Use InterfaceName.super.method() to choose implementation." },
      { id:"ip4", question:"Can constructor be inherited/overridden?", answer:"No, constructors cannot be inherited or overridden in Java. Each class has its own constructors that are responsible for initializing that class's instance variables and establishing its invariants. Constructors are fundamentally different from regular methods — they are initialization blocks, not members of the class.\n\nWhy constructors are not inherited: If a Child class inherited Parent's constructor Parent(String name), calling new Child('someName') would invoke Parent's constructor, which only knows how to initialize Parent's fields — it would leave Child's fields uninitialized. This would violate the invariant that a constructor fully initializes its class's state. Each class must define how its own state is initialized.\n\nHow the child accesses parent initialization: The child class calls the parent's constructor using super(args) as the first statement in its own constructor. This ensures the parent's state is properly initialized before the child initializes its own state. If you don't write super() explicitly, the compiler inserts a no-arg super() call automatically. However, if the parent has no default (no-arg) constructor, you MUST explicitly call super(args) with the required arguments — otherwise the compiler raises an error.\n\nKey rules: (1) super() must be the first statement in the constructor, (2) Each constructor can call only one other constructor (either super() for parent or this() for another constructor in the same class), (3) Constructor chaining ensures proper initialization from Object class down to the most specific subclass, (4) Access modifiers on constructors control instantiation — a private constructor prevents external instantiation (used in singleton pattern, utility classes, and factory methods).", code:`class Parent { Parent(String n) { } }\nclass Child extends Parent {\n    Child() { super("default"); } // must call parent\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Constructors are initialization blocks, not members. Not inherited. If parent has no default constructor, child MUST call super(args). super() must be first statement." },
      { id:"ip5", question:"Composition vs Inheritance?", answer:"Composition and Inheritance are two fundamental techniques for reusing code and establishing relationships between classes in OOP, but they serve different purposes and have different trade-offs.\n\nInheritance (is-a relationship): A class extends another class to acquire its properties and behaviors. It establishes a tight coupling between parent and child — the child depends on the parent's implementation. Inheritance is static: the relationship is defined at compile time and cannot be changed at runtime. The child class is exposed to changes in the parent class (the Fragile Base Class Problem) — modifying the parent can unexpectedly break the child. Use inheritance when there is a genuine 'is-a' relationship and the child is truly a more specific version of the parent. Example: Dog is-a Animal.\n\nComposition (has-a relationship): A class contains a reference to another class and delegates behavior to it. The containing class does not extend the contained class — it simply uses its functionality. Composition is dynamic: the contained object can be replaced at runtime (e.g., via dependency injection or setter methods), providing flexibility. Changes to the contained class don't break the containing class as long as the interface contract is maintained. Use composition when you need to reuse functionality without a strict 'is-a' relationship. Example: Car has-a Engine.\n\nWhy prefer composition: (1) Loose coupling — the container depends on the contained object's interface, not its implementation, (2) Flexibility — you can change the contained object at runtime (e.g., swap a PetrolEngine for a DieselEngine), (3) Better encapsulation — the container controls exactly what it exposes, (4) Avoids the Fragile Base Class Problem — changes to the contained class don't ripple through the hierarchy, (5) Easier testing — you can mock the contained object in unit tests. The Gang of Four design principle: 'Favor composition over inheritance.' Use inheritance only when you need polymorphism through a common base type.", code:`// Inheritance (is-a)\nclass Car extends Vehicle { }\n// Composition (has-a)\nclass Car { private Engine engine; }`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Inheritance: tight coupling, static, subclass depends on parent. Composition: loose coupling, dynamic, can change implementation at runtime. Prefer composition: easier to change, better encapsulation, avoids fragile base class." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "exception-handling",
    title: "Exception Handling",
    icon: "⚠️",
    questions: [
      { id:"e1", question:"What is exception handling? Checked vs Unchecked?", answer:"Exception handling is Java's mechanism for managing runtime errors and abnormal conditions in a structured, predictable way. It allows programs to detect errors, handle them gracefully (recover or report), and continue execution rather than crashing. Java uses a try-catch-finally model where code that might fail is placed in a try block, error handling logic is in catch blocks, and cleanup code goes in finally.\n\nThe Java exception hierarchy: Throwable is the root class. It has two direct subclasses: Error and Exception. Exception is further divided into Checked Exceptions and Unchecked Exceptions (RuntimeException and its subclasses).\n\nChecked Exceptions: Exceptions that the compiler FORCES you to handle — either with a try-catch block or by declaring them in the method signature with the throws keyword. These represent conditions that a reasonable application might want to recover from (e.g., file not found, network timeout, database connection failure). The compiler ensures that every checked exception is either caught or declared, preventing unhandled exceptions from slipping through. Examples: IOException, SQLException, ClassNotFoundException, InterruptedException. Use checked exceptions for recoverable conditions where the caller can take meaningful action.\n\nUnchecked Exceptions (RuntimeException and its subclasses): Exceptions that the compiler does NOT enforce handling of. These represent programming errors or logic bugs that should be fixed in code rather than caught at runtime. Examples: NullPointerException, ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException, ArithmeticException, ClassCastException, IllegalArgumentException. Use unchecked exceptions for conditions that indicate bugs (misuse of API, invalid arguments, null references).\n\nErrors: Serious problems that are not meant to be caught or recovered from. They indicate JVM-level failures. Examples: OutOfMemoryError, StackOverflowError, NoClassDefFoundError. Applications should NOT catch Errors — they should be prevented by fixing root causes (increase heap size, fix infinite recursion, fix classpath).\n\nThe debate: Some developers argue checked exceptions are overused and create verbose code (every method must declare or catch them). Modern frameworks (Spring, Hibernate) favor unchecked exceptions for cleaner APIs. The guideline: use checked for recoverable business conditions, unchecked for programming errors.", code:`// Checked — must catch or declare\ntry { new FileReader("file.txt"); }\ncatch (IOException e) { }\n// Unchecked — not enforced\nint[] a=new int[3]; a[5]=10; // ArrayIndexOutOfBounds`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Checked: must catch or throws. Examples: IOException, SQLException. Unchecked: RuntimeException subclasses, not enforced. Examples: NPE, ArithmeticException. Error: serious JVM issues, don't catch." },
      { id:"e2", question:"throw vs throws?", answer:"throw and throws are two distinct keywords in Java's exception handling mechanism, used at different points in the exception lifecycle.\n\nthrow (statement): Used inside a method or block to explicitly throw an exception at runtime. It is followed by an exception OBJECT (an instance of Throwable or its subclass). You create the exception object with new, optionally provide a message, and throw it. Execution of the current method stops immediately at the throw statement, and the exception propagates up the call stack. You can throw only ONE exception at a time. Example: throw new IllegalArgumentException('Age cannot be negative'); — creates and throws the exception in one line.\n\nthrows (clause): Used in a method signature to DECLARE that the method might throw one or more checked exceptions. It does not throw an exception — it is a compile-time contract that warns callers they need to handle or further declare the listed exceptions. throws is followed by exception CLASS names (not objects), separated by commas. A method that actually throws a checked exception must either catch it or declare it with throws. Example: void readFile() throws IOException, FileNotFoundException { ... } — tells callers this method might throw these exceptions.\n\nKey differences: (1) throw is used inside a method body; throws appears in the method signature, (2) throw is followed by an exception object (new Exception()); throws is followed by exception class names (Exception), (3) throw actually transfers control; throws is a declaration that warns callers, (4) throw can throw only one exception; throws can declare multiple exceptions, (5) throw is used for both checked and unchecked exceptions; throws is primarily needed for checked exceptions (unchecked don't require declaration, though you can declare them).", code:`void setAge(int age) {\n    if(age<0) throw new IllegalArgumentException();\n}\nvoid read() throws IOException { new FileReader("f"); }`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"throw: inside method, throws one exception. throws: in signature, declares multiple. throw=new exception object. throws=exception class names." },
      { id:"e3", question:"What is the finally block?", answer:"The finally block is a block of code that always executes after a try-catch block, regardless of whether an exception was thrown, caught, or not caught at all. It is the primary mechanism for guaranteeing cleanup operations (closing files, releasing resources, unlocking mutexes, etc.) in Java's exception handling model.\n\nWhen finally executes: (1) If no exception occurs in try — finally runs after try completes normally, (2) If an exception occurs and is caught — finally runs after the catch block completes, (3) If an exception occurs and is NOT caught — finally runs before the exception propagates to the caller, (4) If try or catch has a return statement — finally runs BEFORE the return value is actually returned to the caller.\n\nWhen finally does NOT execute: (1) System.exit() is called — the JVM terminates immediately, (2) The JVM crashes (e.g., infinite recursion causing StackOverflowError that kills the JVM), (3) The thread executing the try-catch-finally is killed or interrupted at the OS level.\n\nCritical pitfall — finally's return overrides try/catch return: If finally contains a return statement, it overrides any return from try or catch. Example: try { return 1; } finally { return 2; } — the method returns 2, not 1. Similarly, if try throws an exception and finally returns, the exception is silently swallowed. This is a dangerous anti-pattern — never use return in finally.\n\nBest practice: Use finally only for cleanup (closing streams, releasing locks). Prefer try-with-resources (Java 7+) over manual finally blocks for AutoCloseable resources — it's cleaner, handles suppressed exceptions properly, and eliminates the risk of finally-related bugs.", code:`try { int r=10/0; }\ncatch(ArithmeticException e) { System.out.println("Caught"); }\nfinally { System.out.println("Always runs"); }`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"finally always runs: with/without exception, even if catch returns. Only skipped: System.exit(), JVM crash. Caution: finally's return overrides try/catch return. Prefer try-with-resources." },
      { id:"e4", question:"What is try-with-resources?", answer:"Try-with-resources is a Java 7+ feature that provides automatic resource management, ensuring that resources (streams, connections, locks) are closed reliably without requiring an explicit finally block. It eliminates the boilerplate and error-prone pattern of manually closing resources in finally blocks.\n\nHow it works: You declare one or more resources in parentheses after the try keyword: try (ResourceType r = new ResourceType(...)) { ... }. Each resource must implement the AutoCloseable interface (or its parent interface Closeable). When the try block completes (normally or with an exception), the JVM automatically calls close() on each resource in REVERSE order of their declaration (last declared, first closed — like a stack).\n\nMultiple resources: try (FileReader fr = new FileReader('f'); BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(fr)) { ... } — br is closed first, then fr. This reverse order ensures that wrapper resources (BufferedReader wrapping FileReader) are closed before their underlying resources.\n\nSuppressed exceptions: If the try block throws an exception AND the close() method also throws an exception, the try block's exception becomes the primary exception, and the close() exception becomes a suppressed exception attached to it. You can access suppressed exceptions via Throwable.getSuppressed(). In the old try-finally pattern, the close() exception would overwrite the try block's exception, losing the original error information.\n\nEffective final requirement (Java 9+): You can use an already-declared resource in try-with-resources if it is effectively final: BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader('f')); try (br) { ... } — cleaner syntax.\n\nAutoCloseable vs Closeable: AutoCloseable (Java 7) is the parent interface — its close() can throw Exception. Closeable (Java 5) extends AutoCloseable — its close() throws only IOException. Implement AutoCloseable for custom resources.", code:`try (FileReader fr=new FileReader("f");\n     BufferedReader br=new BufferedReader(fr)) {\n    br.readLine();\n} catch(IOException e) { }`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Resources in try() auto-closed in reverse order. Must implement AutoCloseable. Suppressed exceptions accessible via getSuppressed(). Prefer over manual finally." },
      { id:"e5", question:"Can you have try without catch?", answer:"Yes, a try block does not require a catch block. Java allows three valid combinations: try-catch, try-finally, and try-catch-finally. Additionally, try-with-resources (Java 7+) can be used without catch. When you use try without catch, the exception is NOT handled locally — it propagates up the call stack to the calling method. However, the finally block (or the auto-close of try-with-resources) still executes before the exception propagates.\n\nUse cases for try without catch: (1) try-finally: When the current method cannot meaningfully handle the exception but must ensure cleanup. Example: void readFile() throws IOException { FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream('f'); try { /* read data */ } finally { fis.close(); } } — the exception propagates, but the stream is always closed. (2) try-with-resources without catch: The cleanest form — resources are auto-closed and the exception propagates. Example: void readFile() throws IOException { try (FileReader fr = new FileReader('f')) { /* read */ } } — no catch, no finally, but fr is guaranteed closed.\n\nImportant: If you use try-finally without catch and the finally block throws an exception, it will mask the original exception from the try block. This is another reason to prefer try-with-resources — it properly handles suppressed exceptions instead of masking them.", code:`void read() throws IOException {\n    try (FileReader fr=new FileReader("f")) {\n        // exception propagates, fr auto-closed\n    }\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Use when current method can't handle exception but must clean up. try-finally or try-with-resources both valid without catch." },
      { id:"e6", question:"How to create custom exception?", answer:"Creating custom exceptions allows you to represent domain-specific error conditions that aren't covered by Java's built-in exception classes. This makes your error handling more expressive and type-safe — callers can catch your specific exception and take targeted action rather than catching generic Exception.\n\nSteps to create a custom exception:\n1. Choose the base class: Extend Exception for a checked exception (caller must handle), or extend RuntimeException for an unchecked exception (caller is not forced to handle). The choice depends on whether the condition is recoverable (checked) or indicates a programming error (unchecked).\n2. Provide constructors: At minimum, provide a no-arg constructor and a constructor that accepts a String message. Also provide a constructor that accepts a cause (another Throwable) for exception chaining. Optionally add constructors with custom fields.\n3. Add custom fields: Include any data that helps the caller understand and handle the error (e.g., an error code, the invalid value, a threshold that was exceeded).\n4. Naming convention: End the class name with 'Exception' (e.g., InsufficientFundsException, InvalidAgeException).\n\nBest practices: (1) Always call super(message) to set the exception message, (2) Provide a constructor that accepts a Throwable cause for exception chaining — new CustomException('message', cause), (3) Make the exception class final if it shouldn't be subclassed, (4) Override toString() if you want custom formatting, (5) Keep the exception immutable — store any custom data in final fields, (6) Don't create custom exceptions when a built-in one conveys the same meaning (e.g., use IllegalArgumentException instead of InvalidParameterException).", code:`class InsufficientFundsException extends Exception {\n    private double amount;\n    InsufficientFundsException(double amt) {\n        super("Insufficient: "+amt);\n        this.amount=amt;\n    }\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Extend Exception for checked (caller must handle), RuntimeException for unchecked. Add custom fields for context. Call super(message). Naming: XxxException." },
      { id:"e7", question:"Error vs Exception?", answer:"Both Error and Exception are direct subclasses of Throwable, but they serve fundamentally different purposes in Java's exception hierarchy.\n\nError: Represents serious, unrecoverable problems at the JVM level that applications should not attempt to catch or handle. Errors indicate conditions that are beyond the application's control — the JVM or the system is in a state where recovery is impossible or impractical. Examples: OutOfMemoryError (JVM ran out of heap space), StackOverflowError (infinite recursion exhausted the call stack), NoClassDefFoundError (class existed at compile time but not at runtime), ThreadDeath (deprecated, thread was forcibly stopped).\n\nException: Represents conditions that a reasonable application might want to catch and recover from. Exceptions are application-level problems — they indicate something went wrong in the program's logic or environment, but the program can potentially handle it and continue. Examples: IOException (file not found, network error), SQLException (database query failed), NullPointerException (called a method on null reference).\n\nKey differences: (1) Error is for JVM-level, system-level problems; Exception is for application-level problems, (2) Errors should NOT be caught — fix the root cause (increase memory, fix recursion, fix classpath); Exceptions should be caught and handled when recovery is possible, (3) Errors are almost always unchecked (no throws declaration needed); Exceptions can be checked or unchecked, (4) Errors rarely need custom subclasses; custom exceptions always extend Exception or RuntimeException.\n\nPractical rule: Never catch Error in application code. If you're catching Throwable, you're almost certainly doing something wrong — it catches both Errors and Exceptions. Catch specific Exception subclasses instead.", code:`// Error — don't catch\n// OutOfMemoryError, StackOverflowError\n// Exception — catch and handle\ntry { int x=10/0; }\ncatch(ArithmeticException e) { }`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Both extend Throwable. Error: JVM-level, not recoverable. Exception: application-level, recoverable. Don't catch Errors—fix root cause." },
      { id:"e8", question:"What is exception propagation?", answer:"Exception propagation is the mechanism by which an uncaught exception travels up the method call stack, searching for a matching catch block. When a method throws an exception and doesn't catch it locally, the JVM terminates that method and propagates the exception to the calling method. If the caller doesn't catch it either, the exception continues propagating up the call stack until it either finds a matching catch block or reaches the main() method. If main() doesn't catch it, the JVM's default handler catches it, prints the stack trace, and terminates the program.\n\nHow it works step by step: If method m3() throws an ArithmeticException, and m3() is called by m2(), which is called by m1(), which is called by main(): the exception propagates m3→m2→m1→main. At each level, the JVM looks for a try-catch that handles ArithmeticException. If found, the exception is caught and handled. If not found, the method terminates and the exception continues upward.\n\nChecked vs Unchecked propagation: Unchecked exceptions (RuntimeException and its subclasses) propagate automatically — no declaration needed. The exception simply moves up the call stack until caught. Checked exceptions must be declared with throws at every method in the call chain that doesn't catch them. If a method throws a checked exception and doesn't catch it, the method MUST declare it with throws, and every caller must either catch it or also declare it with throws. This is the compiler's way of ensuring checked exceptions are always accounted for.\n\nStack trace: When an exception is finally caught (or reaches the JVM), the stack trace shows the complete propagation path — each method and line number from where the exception was thrown to where it was caught. This is invaluable for debugging.", code:`void m3() { throw new ArithmeticException(); }\nvoid m2() { m3(); }\nvoid m1() { m2(); }\nvoid main() { try { m1(); } catch(ArithmeticException e) { } }`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Unchecked auto-propagate. Checked must be declared with throws at each level. If never caught, JVM prints stack trace and terminates." },
      { id:"e9", question:"What are suppressed exceptions?", answer:"Suppressed exceptions are exceptions that are attached to a primary exception when both the try block and a resource's close() method throw exceptions simultaneously. This situation arises specifically with try-with-resources (Java 7+), and the mechanism ensures that neither exception is lost.\n\nThe problem it solves: In the old try-finally pattern, if the try block throws an exception and the finally block (which calls close()) also throws an exception, the finally exception overwrites the try exception — the original exception is completely lost, making debugging very difficult. You'd only see the close() exception with no indication of what went wrong in the try block.\n\nHow try-with-resources handles it: When the try block throws exception A and the close() method throws exception B, exception A becomes the primary exception (thrown to the caller), and exception B is attached to A as a suppressed exception. The caller can access suppressed exceptions via Throwable.getSuppressed(), which returns an array of Throwable objects. Neither exception is lost — the primary exception describes what went wrong in the business logic, and the suppressed exception describes what went wrong during cleanup.\n\nMultiple resources: If try-with-resources declares multiple resources and both the try block and multiple close() methods throw exceptions, the try exception is primary and all close() exceptions are suppressed (in reverse close order).\n\nBest practice: When logging exceptions, always log suppressed exceptions too. Many logging frameworks do this automatically. When creating custom AutoCloseable resources, ensure close() never throws unless absolutely necessary — this minimizes suppressed exceptions.", code:`try (MyResource r=new MyResource()) {\n    throw new RuntimeException("Try");\n} catch(RuntimeException e) {\n    for(Throwable s : e.getSuppressed()) System.out.println(s);\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"In try-with-resources: try exception primary, close() suppressed. Access via getSuppressed(). Traditional try-finally loses the try exception if finally also throws." },
      { id:"e10", question:"final vs finally vs finalize?", answer:"These three terms sound similar but are completely different concepts in Java — they just share the same root word.\n\nfinal (keyword): A modifier that can be applied to variables, methods, and classes with different meanings in each context. (1) final variable: Cannot be reassigned after initialization — makes it a constant. For reference types, the reference is fixed but the object's internal state can still be modified (final List<String> list = new ArrayList<>(); list.add('item') is OK; list = new ArrayList<>() is NOT). (2) final method: Cannot be overridden by subclasses — locks the implementation. Used when the method's behavior must not change in subclasses. (3) final class: Cannot be extended (no subclass). Used for immutable classes (String, Integer, all wrapper classes) and utility classes (Math, System) to prevent subclassing. (4) final parameters: Cannot be reassigned within the method body (rarely used explicitly).\n\nfinally (block): A block that follows try-catch and is guaranteed to execute regardless of whether an exception was thrown or caught. Used for cleanup operations (closing streams, releasing locks, resetting state). The only situations where finally doesn't run: System.exit() or JVM crash. Best practice: prefer try-with-resources over manual finally for resource cleanup.\n\nfinalize (method): A protected method defined in Object class that the garbage collector calls before reclaiming an object's memory. It was intended as a last-resort cleanup mechanism for objects holding native resources. However, finalize() is deeply flawed: (1) No guarantee it will ever be called (GC is non-deterministic), (2) Can be called on objects that are partially constructed, (3) Can resurrect objects (make them reachable again), preventing GC, (4) Performance overhead — objects with finalize require extra GC processing. Deprecated since Java 9. Use try-with-resources or java.lang.ref.Cleaner (Java 9+) instead.\n\nMnemonic: final = constant/lock, finally = cleanup block, finalize = deprecated cleanup method.", code:`final int MAX=100; // can't reassign\ntry { } finally { } // always runs\nclass Old {\n    @Deprecated protected void finalize() { } // don't use\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"final: variable=constant, method=no override, class=no extend. finally: cleanup block. finalize: deprecated since Java 9, unreliable. Use try-with-resources or Cleaners instead." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "collections",
    title: "Collections Framework",
    icon: "📦",
    questions: [
      { id:"c1", question:"What is the Collections Framework?", answer:"The Java Collections Framework (JCF) is a unified architecture for representing and manipulating collections of objects. Introduced in Java 1.2 (JDK 2), it provides a standardized set of interfaces, implementations, and algorithms that eliminate the need for ad-hoc data structures and provide interoperability between different collection types.\n\nThe framework is built on three pillars:\n1. Interfaces: Abstract data types that define the contract for different kinds of collections. The core interfaces form a hierarchy: Collection (root) → List, Set, Queue, Deque. Map stands alone (not a true Collection but part of the framework). Each interface defines the operations its implementations must support (add, remove, contains, size, iterate, etc.).\n2. Implementations: Concrete classes that implement the interfaces using different data structures. List implementations: ArrayList (dynamic array), LinkedList (doubly-linked list), Vector (synchronized dynamic array, legacy). Set implementations: HashSet (hash table), TreeSet (red-black tree, sorted), LinkedHashSet (hash table + linked list, insertion order). Map implementations: HashMap (hash table), TreeMap (red-black tree), LinkedHashMap (hash table + linked list). Queue implementations: PriorityQueue (heap), ArrayDeque (circular array).\n3. Algorithms: Static utility methods in the Collections class that operate on collections: sort (merge sort, stable, O(n log n)), binarySearch (O(log n)), reverse, shuffle, fill, copy, min/max, frequency, disjoint, unmodifiable wrappers, synchronized wrappers.\n\nKey design principles: The framework uses generics for type safety (since Java 5), provides fail-fast iterators (throw ConcurrentModificationException on concurrent modification), and separates interfaces from implementations so you can change implementations without changing code (program to the interface, not the implementation).", code:`List<String> list=new ArrayList<>();\nSet<String> set=new HashSet<>();\nMap<String,Integer> map=new HashMap<>();\nCollections.sort(list);`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Interfaces: Collection, List, Set, Map, Queue. Implementations: ArrayList, LinkedList, HashSet, TreeSet, HashMap, TreeMap. Algorithms: sort, shuffle, reverse, binarySearch." },
      { id:"c2", question:"ArrayList vs LinkedList?", answer:"ArrayList and LinkedList are the two primary List implementations in Java, built on fundamentally different data structures with different performance characteristics.\n\nArrayList: Built on a dynamic array that automatically resizes (grows by 50% when full). Provides O(1) random access via index (get(i) directly computes memory address as base + i * elementSize). Insertion and deletion at the END are amortized O(1) — appending is fast until the array needs resizing. Insertion/deletion at the MIDDLE or BEGINNING is O(n) because all subsequent elements must be shifted right or left. ArrayList has excellent cache locality because elements are stored contiguously in memory — the CPU cache prefetches adjacent elements, making sequential iteration very fast. Memory overhead: just the array plus a small object header — very efficient per element.\n\nLinkedList: Built on a doubly-linked list where each element (Node) stores data plus references to the previous and next nodes. Random access is O(n) — to reach element i, you must traverse from the head (or tail, whichever is closer). Insertion and deletion at the HEAD or TAIL are O(1) — just update a few pointers (addFirst, addLast, removeFirst, removeLast). Insertion/deletion at a KNOWN POSITION (you already have a reference to the node) is O(1), but finding that position is O(n). LinkedList has poor cache locality — nodes are scattered across the heap, causing cache misses during iteration. Memory overhead: each element requires a Node object with two additional references (prev, next) — significantly more memory per element than ArrayList.\n\nWhen to use which: Use ArrayList for almost everything — it's faster for most real-world access patterns (iteration, random access, appending). Use LinkedList only when you need frequent insertions/deletions at the head (queue/deque operations) or when you need to iterate and remove elements simultaneously. In practice, even for queue operations, ArrayDeque outperforms LinkedList.", code:`List<String> al=new ArrayList<>(); // fast get\nal.get(0); // O(1)\nLinkedList<String> ll=new LinkedList<>();\nll.addFirst("A"); // O(1)`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"ArrayList: better cache locality, less memory overhead. Use for most cases. LinkedList: use for frequent head/tail operations. LinkedList insert/delete at known node is O(1) but finding node is O(n)." },
      { id:"c3", question:"HashMap vs TreeMap vs LinkedHashMap?", answer:"These are the three primary Map implementations in Java, each using a different underlying data structure and offering different ordering guarantees.\n\nHashMap: Uses a hash table (array of buckets). Keys are mapped to bucket indices via hashCode(). Provides O(1) average-case performance for get, put, remove, and containsKey. Does NOT maintain any order — iterating over entries gives unpredictable ordering that can change when the map is resized. Allows one null key and multiple null values. Best for general-purpose key-value storage where order doesn't matter. Default initial capacity is 16, load factor is 0.75 (resizes when 75% full). Not thread-safe.\n\nTreeMap: Uses a Red-Black Tree (self-balancing binary search tree). Keys are stored in sorted order — either natural ordering (keys implement Comparable) or by a custom Comparator provided at construction. Provides O(log n) performance for get, put, remove, and containsKey. Supports navigation methods: firstKey(), lastKey(), higherKey(), lowerKey(), subMap(), headMap(), tailMap(). Does NOT allow null keys (because compareTo() would throw NPE), but allows null values. Use TreeMap when you need sorted keys or range queries. Not thread-safe.\n\nLinkedHashMap: Extends HashMap with a doubly-linked list running through all entries. Preserves insertion order by default — iterating gives entries in the order they were added. Can also be configured for access order (constructor: new LinkedHashMap<>(16, 0.75f, true)) — iterating gives entries from least-recently-accessed to most-recently-accessed, making it ideal for LRU caches. Provides O(1) performance (same as HashMap) plus the linked list overhead. Allows one null key and null values. Slightly more memory than HashMap due to the linked list pointers. Not thread-safe.\n\nThread safety: None of these are thread-safe. For concurrent access, use ConcurrentHashMap.", code:`Map<String,Integer> hm=new HashMap<>(); // no order\nMap<String,Integer> tm=new TreeMap<>(); // sorted keys\nMap<String,Integer> lm=new LinkedHashMap<>(); // insertion order`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"HashMap: general purpose. TreeMap: sorted keys (natural/comparator), no null key. LinkedHashMap: preserves order, can be access-order for LRU cache. All: not thread-safe." },
      { id:"c4", question:"HashSet vs TreeSet vs LinkedHashSet?", answer:"These are the three primary Set implementations in Java, each backed by the corresponding Map implementation (a Set is essentially a Map where values are ignored).\n\nHashSet: Backed by a HashMap. Stores elements using hashing — elements are distributed across buckets based on hashCode(). Provides O(1) average-case performance for add, remove, contains. Does NOT maintain any order — iteration order is unpredictable and can change when the set is resized. Allows one null element. Requires that elements properly override hashCode() and equals() — two elements that are equals() must have the same hashCode(). Best for general-purpose uniqueness checking where order doesn't matter. Default initial capacity is 16, load factor is 0.75.\n\nTreeSet: Backed by a TreeMap (Red-Black Tree). Stores elements in sorted order — either natural ordering (elements implement Comparable) or by a custom Comparator. Provides O(log n) performance for add, remove, contains. Supports navigation methods: first(), last(), higher(), lower(), headSet(), tailSet(), subSet(). Does NOT allow null elements (because compareTo() would throw NPE). Elements must be mutually comparable — you cannot add objects of different types that can't be compared. Use TreeSet when you need sorted elements or range queries.\n\nLinkedHashSet: Extends HashSet with a doubly-linked list running through all elements. Preserves insertion order — iterating gives elements in the order they were added. Provides O(1) performance (same as HashSet) with slightly more memory overhead for the linked list. Allows one null element. Ideal when you need uniqueness AND predictable iteration order, such as maintaining a set of recently used items in insertion order.", code:`Set<String> hs=new HashSet<>(); // no order\nSet<String> ts=new TreeSet<>(); // sorted\nSet<String> ls=new LinkedHashSet<>(); // insertion order`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"HashSet: fastest, allows null. TreeSet: sorted, no null, elements must be Comparable. LinkedHashSet: preserves insertion order, allows null." },
      { id:"c5", question:"Comparable vs Comparator?", answer:"Comparable and Comparator are two interfaces in Java that define strategies for ordering objects, but they differ in design philosophy and usage.\n\nComparable (java.lang.Comparable<T>): Defines the natural ordering of objects within the class itself. A class implements Comparable and overrides the compareTo(T o) method, which returns negative if this < o, zero if this == o, and positive if this > o. The natural ordering is the default/default sort order — Collections.sort() and Arrays.sort() use it automatically. A class can have only ONE natural ordering (single compareTo method). Example: String implements Comparable<String> — 'apple'.compareTo('banana') returns a negative number because 'apple' comes before 'banana' lexicographically. Integer, Double, and all wrapper classes implement Comparable with their natural numeric ordering.\n\nComparator (java.util.Comparator<T>): Defines a custom ordering strategy OUTSIDE the class being compared. A separate class (often a lambda) implements Comparator and overrides the compare(T o1, T o2) method. You can create unlimited Comparators for the same class — different sorting strategies for different use cases. Example: Comparator<Employee> bySalary = Comparator.comparing(Employee::getSalary); Comparator<Employee> byName = Comparator.comparing(Employee::getName); — two different orderings for the same class.\n\nKey differences: (1) Comparable is implemented by the class being compared; Comparator is a separate class, (2) Comparable defines the single natural/default ordering; Comparator defines custom orderings, (3) Comparable uses compareTo(T); Comparator uses compare(T, T), (4) Comparable is in java.lang; Comparator is in java.util, (5) Collections.sort(list) uses Comparable; Collections.sort(list, comparator) uses Comparator.\n\nBest practice: Implement Comparable for the most obvious/default ordering. Use Comparator for alternative orderings, multi-field sorting, and when you can't modify the original class.", code:`class Emp implements Comparable<Emp> {\n    int salary;\n    public int compareTo(Emp o) { return salary-o.salary; }\n}\nComparator<Emp> byName=Comparator.comparing(e->e.name);`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Comparable: java.lang, compareTo(T), defined in class, one per class. Comparator: java.util, compare(T,T), separate class, unlimited. Use Comparable for default order, Comparator for alternatives." },
      { id:"c6", question:"How does HashMap work internally?", answer:"HashMap is the most commonly used Map implementation and understanding its internal mechanics is crucial for writing efficient Java code.\n\nData structure: HashMap uses an array of buckets (Node<K,V>[] table). Each bucket is a slot that can hold a linked list (or tree) of entries. Default initial capacity is 16, load factor is 0.75 (resizes when number of entries > capacity * 0.75).\n\nput(key, value) operation step by step:\n1. Compute hash: int hash = key.hashCode() is called, then HashMap applies a secondary hash function (hash ^ (hash >>> 16)) to spread bits and reduce collisions.\n2. Compute bucket index: int index = hash & (capacity - 1) — bitwise AND with (capacity-1) is equivalent to hash % capacity but faster. This is why capacity is always a power of 2.\n3. Check bucket: If the bucket is empty, create a new Node and place it there.\n4. Collision handling: If the bucket is occupied, traverse the chain: (a) If key.equals(existingKey), replace the value (update), (b) If no match, add a new Node to the chain.\n5. Treeification: If a bucket's chain length exceeds 8 (TREEIFY_THRESHOLD) AND the total capacity is at least 64, the linked list is converted to a Red-Black Tree for O(log n) performance instead of O(n) in that bucket. If the tree shrinks below 6 nodes (UNTREEIFY_THRESHOLD), it reverts to a linked list.\n6. Resize: When size > capacity * loadFactor, the array is doubled (new capacity = old * 2) and ALL entries are rehashed (redistributed) to new buckets.\n\nCritical contract: You MUST override hashCode() AND equals() together. Rule: equal objects (equals() returns true) MUST have equal hashCodes. If two equal objects have different hashCodes, they'll end up in different buckets and HashMap won't find the existing key (causing duplicates). A bad hashCode() that returns the same value for all objects puts everything in one bucket, degrading performance to O(n).", code:`put(key, value):\n1. hash = key.hashCode()\n2. index = hash & (capacity-1)\n3. If empty → new Node\n4. If occupied → equals() check\n5. If chain>8 → treeify (TreeMap)`, codeLanguage:"plaintext", explanation:"Key: always override hashCode() AND equals() together. Equal objects must have equal hashCodes. Bad hashCode=all entries in one bucket=O(n). Default capacity=16, loadFactor=0.75." },
      { id:"c7", question:"What is ConcurrentHashMap?", answer:"ConcurrentHashMap is the thread-safe replacement for HashMap (and Hashtable) in the java.util.concurrent package. It allows multiple threads to read and write concurrently without locking the entire map, providing much higher throughput than synchronized maps.\n\nHow it achieves thread safety:\nJava 7 implementation: Used a segment-based approach. The map was divided into 16 segments (each essentially a small HashMap). Each segment had its own lock. Operations only locked the relevant segment, allowing up to 16 threads to write concurrently (one per segment). Read operations were lock-free.\n\nJava 8+ implementation (current): Uses a more granular approach. The bucket array is the primary structure. For most write operations, ConcurrentHashMap uses CAS (Compare-And-Swap) operations — a lock-free technique where a thread atomically updates a variable only if its current value matches the expected value. If CAS fails (another thread modified it), the thread retries. For cases where CAS isn't sufficient (e.g., bucket is already a tree), it falls back to synchronized on the bucket head (only that one bucket is locked, not the whole map). Read operations are completely lock-free — they read volatile variables that are always consistent.\n\nKey features: (1) Null keys and values are NOT allowed (unlike HashMap) — null would create ambiguity in concurrent reads, (2) Provides atomic compound operations: putIfAbsent(), computeIfAbsent(), computeIfPresent(), merge(), compute() — these perform check-then-act atomically without external synchronization, (3) Iterators are weakly consistent — they reflect the map's state at some point during iteration but may not show concurrent modifications. They never throw ConcurrentModificationException, (4) Size calculations use approximate methods for performance — exact counts would require locking the entire map.\n\nWhen to use: Any time multiple threads need to access a shared map. ConcurrentHashMap should be the default choice for concurrent maps — it outperforms Collections.synchronizedMap() and Hashtable significantly.", code:`ConcurrentMap<String,Integer> map=new ConcurrentHashMap<>();\nmap.putIfAbsent("A",1);\nmap.computeIfAbsent("B", k->2);`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Java 7: segments (16 by default). Java 8+: CAS + synchronized on bucket head. Reads are lock-free. Null keys/values NOT allowed. Use for multi-threaded scenarios." },
      { id:"c8", question:"What is fail-fast vs fail-safe iterator?", answer:"Fail-fast and fail-safe describe two strategies for handling concurrent modification of collections during iteration.\n\nFail-fast iterators: Throw ConcurrentModificationException (CME) immediately if the collection is structurally modified (add, remove, clear) after the iterator was created, except through the iterator's own remove() method. This is the behavior of most standard collections: ArrayList, HashMap, HashSet, LinkedList, etc. How it works: Each collection maintains a modification counter (modCount). When the iterator is created, it records the current modCount. On each next() call, the iterator compares its recorded modCount with the collection's current modCount — if they differ, CME is thrown. This is a best-effort mechanism — the JVM does NOT guarantee throwing CME (it's not synchronized), but it tries to detect problems early. Fail-fast is designed to prevent undefined behavior from iterating over a collection that's changing under you.\n\nFail-safe iterators: Do NOT throw ConcurrentModificationException. They work on a copy or snapshot of the collection's data, so concurrent modifications to the original collection don't affect the iteration. Examples: ConcurrentHashMap's iterator (weakly consistent — reflects state at some point), CopyOnWriteArrayList's iterator (iterates over a snapshot taken at iterator creation — never sees modifications made after creation). The trade-off: fail-safe iterators may show stale data (not reflecting the latest modifications), and copying has memory/performance overhead.\n\nWhen to use which: Use fail-fast collections (ArrayList, HashMap) in single-threaded contexts — they catch bugs early. Use fail-safe collections (ConcurrentHashMap, CopyOnWriteArrayList) in multi-threaded contexts where concurrent modification is expected. Never modify a collection during for-each iteration (which uses fail-fast iterators) — use Iterator.remove() or removeIf() instead.", code:`// Fail-fast: ArrayList, HashMap\nList<String> list=new ArrayList<>();\nfor(String s:list) { list.add("x"); } // CME!\n// Fail-safe: ConcurrentHashMap, CopyOnWriteArrayList\nConcurrentMap<String,Integer> cm=new ConcurrentHashMap<>();\nfor(String k:cm.keySet()) { cm.put("x",1); } // OK`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Fail-fast: checks modCount, throws CME. Most standard collections. Fail-safe: iterates on snapshot/copy. ConcurrentHashMap, CopyOnWriteArrayList. Fail-safe may show stale data." },
      { id:"c9", question:"What is the difference between List and Set?", answer:"List and Set are both sub-interfaces of Collection, but they enforce fundamentally different contracts regarding ordering and duplicates.\n\nList: An ordered collection (also called a sequence) that allows DUPLICATE elements and maintains INSERTION ORDER. Elements can be accessed by their integer index (0-based). The List contract guarantees that elements appear in the order they were added, and you can insert, access, or remove elements at specific positions. Key operations: get(index), add(index, element), set(index, element), remove(index), indexOf(element), lastIndexOf(element), listIterator(). Implementations: ArrayList (dynamic array, best for random access), LinkedList (doubly-linked list, best for head/tail operations), Vector (synchronized ArrayList, legacy — avoid). Use List when: order matters, duplicates are expected, you need index-based access.\n\nSet: A collection that does NOT allow duplicate elements. At most one null element (implementation-dependent). Set does NOT guarantee order — HashSet is unordered, TreeSet is sorted, LinkedHashSet preserves insertion order. The Set contract is based on mathematical set theory — add() returns false if the element already exists (as determined by equals()). Key operations: add(element), contains(element), remove(element). Implementations: HashSet (hash table, fastest, unordered), TreeSet (red-black tree, sorted, no null), LinkedHashSet (hash table + linked list, insertion order). Use Set when: uniqueness matters, duplicates must be prevented, you need to test membership (contains is O(1) in HashSet).\n\nKey differences: (1) List allows duplicates; Set does not, (2) List maintains insertion order; Set may or may not (depends on implementation), (3) List supports index-based access; Set does not, (4) List has ListIterator (bidirectional); Set has only Iterator (forward only), (5) Adding a duplicate in List adds another copy; adding a duplicate in Set is silently ignored (add() returns false).", code:`List<String> list=new ArrayList<>();\nlist.add("A"); list.add("A"); // [A, A]\nSet<String> set=new HashSet<>();\nset.add("A"); set.add("A"); // [A] only`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"List: ArrayList, LinkedList, Vector. Allows duplicates, maintains order, positional access. Set: HashSet, TreeSet, LinkedHashSet. No duplicates, HashSet unordered, TreeSet sorted." },
      { id:"c10", question:"What is the difference between Iterator and ListIterator?", answer:"Iterator and ListIterator are both interfaces for traversing collections, but ListIterator provides significantly more functionality and is restricted to List collections only.\n\nIterator (java.util.Iterator<E>): A universal cursor for traversing ANY Collection (List, Set, Queue, Map via entrySet/keySet/values). It provides three methods: hasNext() (returns true if more elements exist), next() (returns the next element and advances the cursor), remove() (removes the last element returned by next() — optional operation, must be called after next()). Iterator moves in ONE direction only: forward. It can only REMOVE elements during traversal — you cannot add or replace elements. The remove() method can be called only ONCE per next() call. Iterator is the standard way to traverse collections in Java — the enhanced for-loop (for-each) uses Iterator internally.\n\nListIterator (java.util.ListIterator<E>): Extends Iterator with bidirectional traversal and element modification capabilities. Available ONLY for List collections (obtained via list.listIterator() or list.listIterator(index)). Additional methods: hasPrevious() (returns true if elements exist before the cursor), previous() (moves backward and returns the element), nextIndex() (returns index of next element), previousIndex() (returns index of previous element), add(E e) (inserts element at the cursor position — shifts existing elements right), set(E e) (replaces the last element returned by next() or previous()).\n\nKey differences: (1) Iterator works with any Collection; ListIterator works only with List, (2) Iterator is forward-only; ListIterator is bidirectional, (3) Iterator can only remove; ListIterator can add, set, and remove, (4) Iterator has no index info; ListIterator provides nextIndex/previousIndex, (5) ListIterator extends Iterator — all Iterator functionality is available in ListIterator plus more.\n\nUse Iterator for simple forward traversal of any collection. Use ListIterator when you need to traverse a List bidirectionally, modify elements during traversal, or insert at specific positions.", code:`// Iterator\nIterator<String> it=list.iterator();\nwhile(it.hasNext()) { it.next(); it.remove(); }\n// ListIterator\nListIterator<String> li=list.listIterator();\nli.add("X"); li.set("Y"); li.previous();`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Iterator: hasNext/next/remove, works with any Collection. ListIterator: hasPrevious/previous/add/set/nextIndex/previousIndex, List only. ListIterator extends Iterator." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "multithreading",
    title: "Multithreading",
    icon: "🔀",
    questions: [
      { id:"mt1", question:"What is multithreading? How to create a thread?", answer:"Multithreading: executing multiple threads simultaneously. Create thread by: extending Thread, implementing Runnable, or using Callable+Future.", code:`// Method 1: Extend Thread\nclass MyThread extends Thread {\n    public void run() { System.out.println("Thread: "+getName()); }\n}\nnew MyThread().start();\n\n// Method 2: Implement Runnable\nThread t=new Thread(() -> System.out.println("Runnable"));\nt.start();\n\n// Method 3: Callable + Future\nExecutorService es=Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2);\nFuture<Integer> f=es.submit(() -> 42);\nSystem.out.println(f.get()); // 42`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Thread: override run(), call start(). Runnable: functional interface, better (can extend another class). Callable: returns value, can throw exception. ExecutorService: thread pool management. Always call start(), not run() directly." },
      { id:"mt2", question:"Thread vs Runnable?", answer:"Thread is a class. Runnable is an interface. Prefer Runnable: can extend another class, separation of concerns, usable with executor frameworks.", code:`// Thread — must extend Thread (single inheritance)\nclass MyThread extends Thread {\n    public void run() { /* task */ }\n}\n// Runnable — implement interface (can extend other class)\nclass MyTask implements Runnable {\n    public void run() { /* task */ }\n}\nnew Thread(new MyTask()).start();`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Runnable preferred: Java doesn't support multiple inheritance, implementing Runnable leaves extends available. Each Thread has significant overhead; Runnable decouples task from thread. Runnable works with ExecutorService." },
      { id:"mt3", question:"What is the synchronized keyword?", answer:"synchronized controls access to shared resources by only allowing one thread at a time into a block/method.", code:`// Synchronized method\nsynchronized void increment() { count++; }\n// Synchronized block\nvoid increment() {\n    synchronized(this) { count++; }\n}\n// Static synchronized (class-level lock)\nstatic synchronized void decrement() { count--; }`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Instance method: locks on this object. Static method: locks on Class object. Block: locks on specified object. Only one thread can hold a lock at a time. Other threads block waiting. Avoid over-synchronization—causes contention." },
      { id:"mt4", question:"What is the difference between wait() and sleep()?", answer:"wait(): releases lock, must be called in synchronized block, notified by notify(). sleep(): keeps lock, doesn't need synchronized, wakes after time.", code:`// wait() — releases lock\nsynchronized(lock) {\n    while(!condition) lock.wait(); // releases lock\n    // do work\n}\n// sleep() — keeps lock\nThread.sleep(1000); // doesn't release lock`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"wait: Object method, releases lock, needs notify/notifyAll to wake, must be in synchronized. sleep: Thread method, keeps lock, auto-wakes after time, anywhere. wait is for inter-thread communication; sleep is for pause." },
      { id:"mt5", question:"notify() vs notifyAll()?", answer:"notify(): wakes ONE waiting thread (arbitrary). notifyAll(): wakes ALL waiting threads. Both must be called in synchronized context.", code:`synchronized(lock) {\n    condition=true;\n    lock.notify();    // one random thread\n    lock.notifyAll(); // all waiting threads\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"notify: one thread woken, others still wait. Risk: wrong thread wakes, others starve. notifyAll: all woken, they compete for lock. Safer, use when multiple threads wait. Both must be in synchronized on same object." },
      { id:"mt6", question:"What is a deadlock? How to prevent it?", answer:"Deadlock: two+ threads each wait for a lock held by the other. Prevent by: consistent lock ordering, timeout, avoiding nested locks.", code:`// Deadlock scenario\nThread1: lock A → lock B\nThread2: lock B → lock A\n// Both wait forever!\n\n// Prevention: always lock in same order\n// Both threads: lock A → lock B (consistent order)`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Causes: circular wait, inconsistent lock ordering. Prevent: 1) Lock in consistent order, 2) Use tryLock() with timeout, 3) Avoid nested locks, 4) Use higher-level concurrency utilities (java.util.concurrent)." },
      { id:"mt7", question:"What is the volatile keyword?", answer:"volatile ensures variable reads/writes go directly to main memory (not cached). Guarantees visibility across threads but NOT atomicity.", code:`class Shared {\n    volatile boolean running=true;\n    void stop() { running=false; } // visible to all threads\n}\n// Without volatile, thread may cache running=true forever`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"volatile: visibility guarantee (one thread writes, all see it). No atomicity (count++ still unsafe—use AtomicInteger). Prevents instruction reordering. Use for flags, one-way state. For atomic ops, use AtomicInteger/Long." },
      { id:"mt8", question:"What is the ExecutorService framework?", answer:"ExecutorService manages thread pools. Submit tasks, get Futures, manage lifecycle. Replaces manual thread creation.", code:`ExecutorService es=Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);\nFuture<String> f=es.submit(() -> "result");\nSystem.out.println(f.get());\nes.shutdown();\n// Types: newFixedThreadPool, newCachedThreadPool,\n// newSingleThreadExecutor, newScheduledThreadPool`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Fixed: constant pool size. Cached: creates as needed, reuses idle. Single: one thread, sequential. Scheduled: delayed/periodic tasks. Always shutdown() when done. submit() returns Future; execute() doesn't." },
      { id:"mt9", question:"What is the difference between Callable and Runnable?", answer:"Runnable: no return value, no checked exception. Callable: returns value via Future, can throw checked exception.", code:`// Runnable — void return\nRunnable r=() -> System.out.println("run");\n// Callable — returns value\nCallable<Integer> c=() -> 42;\nFuture<Integer> f=es.submit(c);\nint result=f.get(); // 42`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Runnable: void run(), no checked exceptions. Callable: V call(), returns V, can throw Exception. Callable used with Future for async results. Both functional interfaces since Java 8." },
      { id:"mt10", question:"What is CountDownLatch?", answer:"Synchronization aid: one or more threads wait until a set of operations completes. Count is decremented; threads proceed when count reaches 0.", code:`CountDownLatch latch=new CountDownLatch(3);\n// Worker threads\nnew Thread(() -> { work(); latch.countDown(); }).start();\nnew Thread(() -> { work(); latch.countDown(); }).start();\nnew Thread(() -> { work(); latch.countDown(); }).start();\nlatch.await(); // blocks until count=0\nSystem.out.println("All done!");`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"countDown(): decrements counter. await(): blocks until counter=0. One-time use (cannot reset). Use for: waiting for N services to start, parallel task completion. For reusable barrier, use CyclicBarrier." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "inner-classes",
    title: "Inner Classes & Lambda",
    icon: "🎯",
    questions: [
      { id:"ic1", question:"What are the types of inner classes in Java?", answer:"Java defines four types of nested classes, each with different access rules, use cases, and scoping:\n\n1. Member Inner Class (Non-static nested class): Defined at the member level of the outer class, inside the class body but outside any method. It has an implicit reference to the enclosing outer class instance (Outer.this), which means it can access all members of the outer class including private fields and methods. To create an instance, you need an outer instance: Outer outer = new Outer(); Outer.Inner inner = outer.new Inner();. Use for: iterators in collections, callbacks that need outer class access, helper classes tightly coupled to the outer class.\n\n2. Static Nested Class: Defined with the static modifier at the member level. It does NOT have a reference to the outer class instance — it cannot access non-static members of the outer class directly. It can be instantiated without an outer instance: Outer.Nested nested = new Outer.Nested();. Use for: builder patterns (e.g., Pizza.Builder), helper classes that don't need outer instance access, logically grouping classes that belong together.\n\n3. Local Inner Class: Defined inside a method or block of code. Its scope is limited to that method — it cannot be used outside. It can access the method's local variables, but only if they are effectively final (Java 8+) or declared final. Use for: creating a class that's needed only within one method, implementing a callback within a method.\n\n4. Anonymous Inner Class: A local class without a name — declared and instantiated in a single expression using the new keyword with an interface or abstract class. It combines class definition and instantiation in one step. It cannot have a constructor (no name = no constructor name). Before Java 8, anonymous inner classes were the primary way to pass behavior (e.g., new Runnable() { public void run() { ... } }). Since Java 8, lambdas replace anonymous inner classes for functional interfaces — but anonymous classes are still needed when implementing abstract classes or interfaces with multiple abstract methods.", code:`class Outer {\n    class Inner { }                    // member\n    static class Nested { }           // static nested\n    void method() {\n        class Local { }               // local\n        Runnable r=new Runnable() {   // anonymous\n            public void run() { }\n        };\n    }\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Member: has access to outer instance. Static nested: no outer instance needed. Local: inside method, limited scope. Anonymous: no name, one-time use. Java 8+: lambdas replace many anonymous inner classes." },
      { id:"ic2", question:"What is a functional interface?", answer:"A functional interface is an interface that contains exactly ONE abstract method. This single abstract method (SAM) is what makes the interface a target for lambda expressions and method references. The concept was formalized in Java 8 to enable the lambda feature.\n\nKey rules: (1) Exactly one abstract method — this is the contract. (2) Can have any number of default methods (with implementation) — they don't count toward the single abstract method limit. (3) Can have any number of static methods — they also don't count. (4) Methods from java.lang.Object (equals, hashCode, toString) don't count if declared abstract — an interface declaring these still qualifies as functional. (5) @FunctionalInterface annotation is optional but recommended — it causes a compile error if the interface accidentally gets a second abstract method, acting as a safety net.\n\nWhy functional interfaces matter: Lambda expressions in Java are not standalone functions — they are implementations of functional interfaces. When you write () -> System.out.println('hi'), the compiler infers which functional interface to implement based on the context (target typing). The lambda provides the body of the single abstract method.\n\nCommon functional interfaces in the JDK: Runnable (void run()), Callable<V> (V call()), Comparable<T> (int compareTo(T)), Comparator<T> (int compare(T,T)), ActionListener (void actionPerformed(ActionEvent)), and all interfaces in java.util.function (Predicate, Function, Consumer, Supplier, etc.).\n\nBest practice: Always add @FunctionalInterface when designing a functional interface — it documents intent and prevents accidental addition of a second abstract method by a future developer.", code:`@FunctionalInterface\ninterface Printable {\n    void print(String s);\n    // default and static methods OK\n    default void log() { }\n    static void info() { }\n}\nPrintable p=s -> System.out.println(s);`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"One abstract method required. @FunctionalInterface is optional but recommended (compiler check). Examples: Runnable, Callable, Comparator, Predicate, Function, Consumer, Supplier." },
      { id:"ic3", question:"What is a lambda expression?", answer:"A lambda expression is a concise way to represent an anonymous function that can be passed as if it were an object. Introduced in Java 8, lambdas enable functional programming in Java by allowing behavior (code) to be treated as data — you can pass functions as method arguments, return them from methods, and store them in variables.\n\nSyntax: (parameters) -> expression or (parameters) -> { statements; }. The arrow -> separates the parameter list from the body. If the body is a single expression, the return keyword and braces are optional (the expression's value is implicitly returned). If the body has multiple statements, braces and an explicit return are required.\n\nType inference: The compiler infers the types of lambda parameters from the target type (the functional interface). You don't need to declare types explicitly: (a, b) -> a + b instead of (Integer a, Integer b) -> a + b. For a single parameter with inferred type, parentheses are optional: x -> x * 2.\n\nHow lambdas work: A lambda expression is an implementation of a functional interface. When you write Runnable r = () -> System.out.println('hi'), the compiler creates an implementation of Runnable whose run() method executes the lambda body. Unlike anonymous inner classes, lambdas don't create a separate .class file — they use invokedynamic bytecode instruction for better performance.\n\nLambda vs Anonymous Inner Class: (1) Lambdas work only with functional interfaces; anonymous classes work with any interface/abstract class, (2) Lambdas don't have their own scope — 'this' refers to the enclosing class; in anonymous classes, 'this' refers to the anonymous class instance, (3) Lambdas don't create separate .class files; anonymous classes do, (4) Lambdas can't have instance variables or state; anonymous classes can, (5) Lambdas are more concise and readable for simple implementations.", code:`// Anonymous class\nRunnable r1=new Runnable() {\n    public void run() { System.out.println("Hi"); }\n};\n// Lambda\nRunnable r2=() -> System.out.println("Hi");\n// With parameters\nComparator<String> c=(a,b) -> a.length()-b.length();\n// With body\nComparator<String> c2=(a,b) -> {\n    int diff=a.length()-b.length();\n    return diff;\n};`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Syntax: (params) -> expression or (params) -> { body }. Type inference on params. Single param: no parens needed (x -> x*2). Must target a functional interface. Replaces verbose anonymous inner classes." },
      { id:"ic4", question:"What are method references?", answer:"Method references are a shorthand syntax for lambda expressions that call a single existing method. They make code more readable when a lambda's body consists of nothing but a method call. Introduced in Java 8, method references use the :: operator to reference a method without invoking it.\n\nFour types of method references:\n1. Static method reference: ClassName::staticMethod. Equivalent to lambda (args) -> ClassName.staticMethod(args). Example: Function<String, Integer> f = Integer::parseInt; — equivalent to s -> Integer.parseInt(s).\n2. Instance method reference (specific object): instance::method. Equivalent to lambda (args) -> instance.method(args). Example: String s = 'hello'; Supplier<String> sup = s::toUpperCase; — equivalent to () -> s.toUpperCase().\n3. Instance method reference (arbitrary object of a type): ClassName::instanceMethod. Equivalent to lambda (obj, args) -> obj.instanceMethod(args). The first parameter of the functional interface becomes the object on which the method is called. Example: Function<String, Integer> len = String::length; — equivalent to s -> s.length(). Here, the Function's apply() takes a String and calls length() on it.\n4. Constructor reference: ClassName::new. Equivalent to lambda (args) -> new ClassName(args). Example: Supplier<List<String>> list = ArrayList::new; — equivalent to () -> new ArrayList<>(). The constructor chosen depends on the functional interface's method signature.\n\nWhen to use: Use method references when a lambda simply delegates to an existing method — they're more concise and readable. Use lambdas when you need more complex logic, multiple statements, or when the method reference syntax would be ambiguous.", code:`// Static method reference\nFunction<String,Integer> f=Integer::parseInt;\n// Instance method reference (specific object)\nString s="hello";\nSupplier<String> sup=s::toUpperCase;\n// Instance method reference (type parameter)\nFunction<String,Integer> len=String::length;\n// Constructor reference\nSupplier<List<String>> list=ArrayList::new;`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Static: ClassName::staticMethod. Instance: object::method. Type: ClassName::instanceMethod. Constructor: ClassName::new. Equivalent to lambda but more readable when just calling one method." },
      { id:"ic5", question:"What are the core functional interfaces in java.util.function?", answer:"The java.util.function package (introduced in Java 8) defines a set of core functional interfaces that cover the most common function shapes. These are the building blocks for lambda expressions and method references throughout the Java API (especially Streams).\n\nCore interfaces:\n1. Predicate<T>: Takes one input of type T, returns boolean. Represents a condition/test. Method: boolean test(T t). Use for: filtering (stream.filter()), validation, conditional logic. Example: Predicate<String> isEmpty = s -> s.isEmpty();\n2. Function<T, R>: Takes one input of type T, returns result of type R. Represents a transformation. Method: R apply(T t). Use for: mapping (stream.map()), converting types, extracting values. Example: Function<String, Integer> len = s -> s.length();\n3. Consumer<T>: Takes one input of type T, returns nothing (void). Represents a side-effect operation. Method: void accept(T t). Use for: forEach(), printing, logging, storing. Example: Consumer<String> print = s -> System.out.println(s);\n4. Supplier<T>: Takes no input, returns a result of type T. Represents a factory or lazy value provider. Method: T get(). Use for: lazy evaluation, creating objects, default values. Example: Supplier<Double> random = () -> Math.random();\n\nBi-variants (two arguments): BiPredicate<T,U> (T,U → boolean), BiFunction<T,U,R> (T,U → R), BiConsumer<T,U> (T,U → void). No BiSupplier (two inputs would make it not a supplier).\n\nSpecialized variants: UnaryOperator<T> extends Function<T,T> (input and output same type, e.g., String::toLowerCase). BinaryOperator<T> extends BiFunction<T,T,T> (two same-type inputs, same-type output, e.g., Math::max). Primitive variants avoid autoboxing overhead: IntPredicate, IntFunction<R>, IntConsumer, IntSupplier, LongPredicate, DoubleFunction, etc. These use primitive types directly for better performance in hot loops.", code:`Predicate<String> isEmpty=s -> s.isEmpty();\nFunction<String,Integer> len=s -> s.length();\nConsumer<String> print=s -> System.out.println(s);\nSupplier<Double> random=() -> Math.random();\nBiFunction<String,String,Integer> cmp=(a,b) -> a.compareTo(b);`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Predicate<T>: T→boolean. Function<T,R>: T→R. Consumer<T>: T→void. Supplier<T>: ()->T. Bi- variants take 2 args. UnaryOperator<T>: T→T. Primitive variants: IntPredicate, IntFunction, etc." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "generics",
    title: "Generics",
    icon: "🔲",
    questions: [
      { id:"g1", question:"What are generics in Java?", answer:"Generics are a Java 5 feature that allows classes, interfaces, and methods to be parameterized with type information. They enable you to write code that works with different data types while providing compile-time type safety — the compiler verifies that only the correct types are used, eliminating runtime ClassCastException errors.\n\nBefore generics (Java 1.4 and earlier): Collections stored Object references, so any type could be added. Retrieving elements required explicit casting, which was error-prone — a ClassCastException would only surface at runtime when the wrong type was cast. Example: List list = new ArrayList(); list.add('hello'); String s = (String) list.get(0); — if someone added an Integer, the cast would fail at runtime.\n\nWith generics: You specify the type at declaration: List<String> list = new ArrayList<>(); list.add('hello'); String s = list.get(0); — no cast needed. The compiler ensures only Strings are added — adding an Integer is a compile error, caught before the code ever runs.\n\nBenefits: (1) Compile-time type safety — errors caught early, not at runtime, (2) Eliminates explicit casting — cleaner, more readable code, (3) Better code reuse — a single generic class/method works for multiple types (e.g., List<T> works for String, Integer, any type), (4) Self-documenting code — List<String> clearly states what it holds, (5) Enables generic algorithms — methods like Collections.sort() work with any Comparable type.\n\nCommon generic types: List<E>, Set<E>, Map<K,V>, Queue<E>, Iterator<E>, Comparable<T>, Comparator<T>, Optional<T>, Stream<T>, Class<T>. The diamond operator <> (Java 7+) lets the compiler infer the generic type from the left side: List<String> list = new ArrayList<>() instead of new ArrayList<String>().", code:`// Without generics\nList list=new ArrayList();\nlist.add("hello");\nString s=(String)list.get(0); // cast needed\n\n// With generics\nList<String> list2=new ArrayList<>();\nlist2.add("hello");\nString s2=list2.get(0); // no cast`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Type safety at compile time. Eliminates runtime ClassCastException. No manual casting. Also used for: Map<K,V>, Comparable<T>, etc. Type erasure: generics info removed at runtime." },
      { id:"g2", question:"What is type erasure?", answer:"Type erasure is Java's implementation strategy for generics — the compiler removes all generic type information during compilation, replacing type parameters with their bounds (Object if unbounded, or the bound type if bounded). At runtime, a List<String> and a List<Integer> are both just List — there is no generic type information available. This was a deliberate design choice for backward compatibility with pre-Java 5 code.\n\nWhat the compiler does: (1) Replaces type parameters with Object (or the bound type): List<String> becomes List, T becomes Object, T extends Number becomes Number, (2) Inserts casts at call sites: when you call list.get(0) on a List<String>, the compiler inserts a cast to String automatically, (3) Generates bridge methods to preserve polymorphism with generic types — these synthetic methods ensure that a class implementing Comparable<MyClass> still correctly overrides the compareTo(Object) method from the raw Comparable interface.\n\nConsequences of type erasure: (1) Cannot do new T() — the compiler doesn't know T's type at runtime, (2) Cannot do instanceof T — runtime type info is erased, (3) Cannot do T.class — no Class object for T at runtime, (4) Cannot create generic arrays: new T[] or new List<String>[] — array component type is erased, making the array unsafe, (5) Cannot have static fields of type T — static members are shared across all type parameterizations, (6) Runtime type checks use raw types: list.getClass() returns ArrayList.class, not ArrayList<String>.class.\n\nWhy erasure: Java 5 needed to be backward compatible with Java 1.4 code that used raw types (List without <String>). Erasure allows both generic and raw type code to coexist — a List<String> compiles to the same bytecode as a raw List, so pre-Java 5 libraries work unchanged. The trade-off is that generics are less powerful than in languages like C++ (templates) or C# (reified generics).", code:`// Source code\nList<String> strings=new ArrayList<>();\nList<Integer> ints=new ArrayList<>();\n// After erasure: both are just List\n// strings.getClass()==ints.getClass() → true\n\n// Bridge methods generated by compiler for polymorphism`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Compiler erases type params→Object (or bound). Inserts casts at call sites. Generates bridge methods for polymorphism. Cannot do: new T(), instanceof T, T.class, static T field. Runtime: no generic type info (reifiable types exception)." },
      { id:"g3", question:"What are bounded type parameters?", answer:"Bounded type parameters restrict the types that can be used as type arguments, ensuring that only types satisfying certain conditions are accepted. This allows generic code to call methods on the type parameter that are guaranteed to exist.\n\nUpper bound (<T extends X>): Restricts T to be X or a subtype of X. The keyword extends is used for both classes and interfaces. With an upper bound, you can call any methods defined on X within the generic method or class. Example: <T extends Number> void sum(List<T> list) — inside this method, you can call Number methods like doubleValue() on list elements because the compiler knows every T is at least a Number. Without the bound, T could be any type, and you couldn't call Number methods.\n\nMultiple bounds: <T extends ClassA & InterfaceB & InterfaceC> — T must satisfy all bounds. The class must come first in the list (if any), followed by interfaces. Example: <T extends Number & Comparable<T>> void sort(List<T> list) — T must be both a Number AND Comparable<T>, allowing the method to use Number methods and compare elements.\n\nLower bound (wildcard only): <? super X> means the type argument must be X or a supertype of X. Lower bounds can only be expressed with wildcards (?), not with type parameters (T). Example: void addAll(List<? super Integer> list) — the list could be List<Integer>, List<Number>, or List<Object>, and you can safely add Integer objects to any of them.\n\nWhy bounds matter: Without bounds, generic code can only use Object methods (toString, equals, hashCode). With bounds, you unlock the methods of the bound type, making generics far more useful. Bounded types also provide stronger compile-time type checking — the compiler rejects inappropriate type arguments early.", code:`// Upper bound\n<T extends Number> void sum(List<T> list)\n// Multiple bounds\n<T extends Number & Comparable<T>> void sort(List<T> list)\n// Lower bound (wildcard only)\nvoid addAll(List<? super Integer> list)`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Upper bound: T extends Class/Interface. Multiple: T extends Class & Interface1 & Interface2. Class must be first. Lower bound: ? super X (wildcard only). Bounded types allow calling methods of the bound." },
      { id:"g4", question:"What is the difference between <? extends T> and <? super T>?", answer:"These are the two bounded wildcard forms in Java generics, and the PECS principle (Producer Extends, Consumer Super) is the key to understanding when to use each.\n\n<? extends T> (Upper Bounded Wildcard): The wildcard type must be T or a subtype of T. This makes the collection a PRODUCER — you can safely READ elements from it (all elements are guaranteed to be at least of type T), but you cannot WRITE to it (the compiler can't guarantee the collection accepts the specific subtype you might try to add). Example: List<? extends Number> could be List<Integer>, List<Double>, or List<Number>. You can read Number from it (every element is a Number), but you can't add Integer — the actual list might be a List<Double> which rejects Integers. The compiler prevents this with a compile error.\n\n<? super T> (Lower Bounded Wildcard): The wildcard type must be T or a supertype of T. This makes the collection a CONSUMER — you can safely WRITE elements of type T to it (the collection accepts T or any supertype, so adding T is always safe), but you cannot safely READ specific types from it (the compiler only knows elements are Object, not T). Example: List<? super Integer> could be List<Integer>, List<Number>, or List<Object>. You can add Integer to any of them, but when you call get(), the compiler only knows it returns Object — you'd need to cast.\n\nPECS Principle (Joshua Bloch, Effective Java): If a parameter is a producer (you read from it), use <? extends T>. If a parameter is a consumer (you write to it), use <? super T>. If it's both a producer and consumer, don't use wildcards — use <T> or the exact type.\n\nClassic example: void copy(List<? extends T> src, List<? super T> dest) — src is a producer (you read from it), dest is a consumer (you write to it). This signature allows copying from List<Integer> to List<Number> or List<Object>, which makes logical sense.", code:`// Producer (read from) → extends\nvoid printAll(List<? extends Number> list) {\n    for(Number n:list) System.out.println(n); // read OK\n    // list.add(1); // COMPILE ERROR — can't write\n}\n// Consumer (write to) → super\nvoid addInts(List<? super Integer> list) {\n    list.add(1); list.add(2); // write OK\n    // Integer i=list.get(0); // COMPILE ERROR — can't read\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"PECS rule: If you READ from collection→? extends T. If you WRITE to collection→? super T. If both→? T (or don't use wildcard). ? extends T=upper bounded wildcard. ? super T=lower bounded wildcard." },
      { id:"g5", question:"Can you create a generic array?", answer:"No, generic array creation is not allowed in Java. You cannot write new T[size] or new List<String>[size]. This restriction is a direct consequence of type erasure and how arrays work in Java.\n\nWhy it's forbidden: Arrays in Java know their component type at runtime and enforce it — if you create a String[], the array will throw ArrayStoreException if you try to store a non-String. But with type erasure, T is erased to Object at runtime. So new T[10] would actually create Object[] at runtime, but the compiler would treat it as T[]. This creates a type safety hole: you could store any type in the Object[] array, bypassing the compile-time type check. The Java designers chose to prevent this at compile time rather than allow it and fail at runtime.\n\nThe specific problem: If generic arrays were allowed, you could write: List<String>[] stringLists = new List<String>[1]; Object[] objects = stringLists; objects[0] = new List<Integer>(); String s = stringLists[0].get(0); — this would cause a ClassCastException at runtime without any compile-time warning. The array stores a List<Integer> but the compiler thinks it's a List<String>.\n\nWorkarounds: (1) Use List<T> instead of T[] — this is the recommended approach. Lists provide all array functionality plus type safety. (2) Use an unchecked cast with @SuppressWarnings: T[] arr = (T[]) new Object[10]; — this works but produces an unchecked warning. (3) Use reflection: T[] arr = (T[]) Array.newInstance(clazz, 10); — this creates a properly typed array at runtime using the Class object. This is the only way to create a truly typed generic array.", code:`// NOT allowed\nT[] array=new T[10]; // compile error\nList<String>[] arr=new List<String>[1]; // error\n\n// Workarounds\nList<T> list=new ArrayList<>(); // use List\n@SuppressWarnings("unchecked")\nT[] arr=(T[])new Object[10]; // unchecked cast\nT[] arr2=(T[])Array.newInstance(clazz,10); // reflection`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Type erasure makes T[] unsafe at runtime (would be Object[] but compiler can't guarantee type safety). Use List<T> instead. If array needed, use reflection with Array.newInstance(clazz, size)." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "io",
    title: "I/O & Serialization",
    icon: "📁",
    questions: [
      { id:"io1", question:"What is the difference between InputStream/OutputStream and Reader/Writer?", answer:"Java's I/O system is divided into two parallel hierarchies: byte streams (InputStream/OutputStream) and character streams (Reader/Writer). They serve different purposes and should be chosen based on the type of data being processed.\n\nByte Streams (InputStream/OutputStream): The original I/O classes from Java 1.0, designed for processing raw binary data byte-by-byte. InputStream is the abstract base class for reading bytes; OutputStream is for writing bytes. They operate on a single byte at a time (read() returns an int 0-255, write(int) writes one byte). Subclasses include FileInputStream/FileOutputStream (file I/O), BufferedInputStream/BufferedOutputStream (buffered I/O), DataInputStream/DataOutputStream (reading/writing primitives), ObjectInputStream/ObjectOutputStream (serialization). Use byte streams for: binary files (images, audio, video, PDF), network protocols, compressed data, any non-text data.\n\nCharacter Streams (Reader/Writer): Introduced in Java 1.1 to properly handle character encoding. Reader is the abstract base class for reading characters; Writer is for writing characters. They operate on characters (read() returns a char, 16-bit Unicode). The key advantage: Reader/Writer handle character encoding automatically — they convert between bytes and characters using the specified charset (UTF-8, ISO-8859-1, etc.). Subclasses include FileReader/FileWriter (file I/O with default encoding), BufferedReader/BufferedWriter (buffered + readLine()), InputStreamReader/OutputStreamWriter (bridge between byte and character streams with explicit encoding). Use character streams for: text files, CSV, JSON, XML, any human-readable content.\n\nThe bridge: InputStreamReader wraps an InputStream and decodes bytes to characters using a charset. OutputStreamWriter wraps an OutputStream and encodes characters to bytes. These are the only classes that connect the two hierarchies. Best practice: Always specify the charset explicitly (new InputStreamReader(fis, StandardCharsets.UTF_8)) rather than relying on the platform default encoding.", code:`// Byte streams\nFileInputStream fis=new FileInputStream("data.bin");\nFileOutputStream fos=new FileOutputStream("out.bin");\n// Character streams\nFileReader fr=new FileReader("text.txt");\nFileWriter fw=new FileWriter("out.txt");`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Byte streams: for binary data (images, audio). Character streams: for text, handle encoding automatically. InputStreamReader bridges byte→char. Always close streams (try-with-resources)." },
      { id:"io2", question:"What is BufferedReader? Why use it?", answer:"BufferedReader is a character stream wrapper that adds buffering — it reads a large chunk of data from the underlying stream into an internal buffer (default 8192 chars), then serves individual read requests from the buffer instead of making a system call each time. This dramatically improves performance because system calls (OS-level file reads) are orders of magnitude slower than reading from memory.\n\nWithout buffering: Every call to FileReader.read() triggers a system call to read one or a few bytes from the file. For a 1MB file read character-by-character, that's potentially millions of system calls — each one involving a context switch from user space to kernel space and back. This is extremely slow.\n\nWith buffering: BufferedReader reads a large chunk (8KB) into memory in one system call. Subsequent read() calls return data from the buffer (memory access, nanoseconds). When the buffer is exhausted, another single system call refills it. For a 1MB file, this reduces system calls from millions to ~125 (1MB / 8KB), a massive improvement.\n\nKey methods: read() reads a single character from the buffer, readLine() reads an entire line (up to \\n, \\r, or \\r\\n) and returns it as a String (null at end of file) — this is the most commonly used method. read(char[] cbuf, int off, int len) reads multiple characters into an array.\n\nChaining pattern: Always wrap the low-level stream: BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader('file.txt')); — FileReader does the actual file reading, BufferedReader adds the buffering layer. Similarly for writing: BufferedWriter bw = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter('out.txt')); — provides newLine() for platform-independent line separators.\n\nBest practice: Always use buffering for file I/O. Unbuffered file reads/writes are a common performance bug. Use try-with-resources to ensure streams are closed.", code:`BufferedReader br=new BufferedReader(new FileReader("file.txt"));\nString line;\nwhile((line=br.readLine())!=null) {\n    System.out.println(line);\n}\nbr.close();`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Without buffer: each read() = system call (slow). With buffer: reads chunk into memory, serves from buffer (fast). BufferedReader: readLine() convenience. BufferedWriter: newLine(). Always chain: BufferedReader(new FileReader())." },
      { id:"io3", question:"What is serialization? How to implement it?", answer:"Serialization is the process of converting an object's state (its non-static, non-transient fields) into a byte stream so it can be stored (file, database), transmitted (network, RMI), or cached. Deserialization is the reverse — reconstructing the object from the byte stream. Java provides built-in serialization through the Serializable interface and ObjectInputStream/ObjectOutputStream classes.\n\nHow to implement: (1) Make the class implement java.io.Serializable — this is a marker interface with no methods. It simply tells the JVM that this class's objects are allowed to be serialized. (2) Add serialVersionUID: private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L; — this version control number ensures that the deserializing class is compatible with the serialized data. If the serialVersionUID doesn't match, InvalidClassException is thrown. If you don't declare one, the JVM generates one automatically based on class structure — but any change to the class (adding a field, changing a method) changes the generated UID, breaking compatibility with previously serialized objects. Always declare it explicitly. (3) Mark fields that should NOT be serialized with the transient keyword (passwords, connections, threads). (4) Use ObjectOutputStream to write: oos.writeObject(myObject); — writes the entire object graph (all non-transient, non-static fields, plus any objects they reference). (5) Use ObjectInputStream to read: MyClass obj = (MyClass) ois.readObject(); — reconstructs the object. A cast is needed because readObject() returns Object.\n\nWhat gets serialized: All non-transient instance fields, all objects referenced by those fields (the entire object graph), the class name and serialVersionUID. What does NOT get serialized: static fields (they belong to the class, not the instance), transient fields (marked to be skipped), any object whose class doesn't implement Serializable (NotSerializableException is thrown).\n\nSecurity concern: Java's default serialization captures the complete internal state of an object, including private fields. It's also vulnerable to deserialization attacks — a malicious byte stream can craft objects that exploit code during deserialization. For security-sensitive applications, prefer alternatives like JSON serialization (Jackson, Gson) or protocol buffers.", code:`class Employee implements Serializable {\n    private static final long serialVersionUID=1L;\n    String name; int id;\n    transient String password; // not serialized\n}\n// Write\nObjectOutputStream oos=new ObjectOutputStream(\n    new FileOutputStream("emp.dat"));\noos.writeObject(new Employee("Alice",1,"secret"));\n// Read\nObjectInputStream ois=new ObjectInputStream(\n    new FileInputStream("emp.dat"));\nEmployee e=(Employee)ois.readObject();`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Serializable: marker interface (no methods). serialVersionUID: version control, prevents InvalidClassException. transient: skip field. Externalizable: custom serialization (readExternal/writeExternal). Not serialized: static fields." },
      { id:"io4", question:"What is the transient keyword?", answer:"The transient keyword in Java is a modifier that marks a field as excluded from serialization. When an object is serialized using ObjectOutputStream, transient fields are NOT written to the byte stream. When the object is deserialized, transient fields are restored to their default values (null for references, 0 for numeric primitives, false for boolean) rather than their original values.\n\nWhy use transient: (1) Sensitive data: Passwords, API keys, security tokens should never be serialized — they could be read by anyone with access to the byte stream. Mark them transient and reconstruct them after deserialization. (2) Non-serializable objects: If a field's class doesn't implement Serializable, serializing the containing object would throw NotSerializableException. Mark the field transient to skip it. Common examples: Thread, Connection, Socket, InputStream, Logger — these are runtime resources that don't make sense to persist. (3) Derived/cached data: Fields that can be recomputed from other fields don't need serialization — mark them transient and recalculate after deserialization. This saves serialization size and time. (4) Large data: Very large fields (caches, buffers) that are expensive to serialize and can be reconstructed should be transient.\n\nImportant: static fields are also not serialized, but for a different reason — static fields belong to the class, not to any individual instance. The transient keyword is only relevant for instance fields. A field that is both static and transient is redundant (static already excludes it).\n\nAfter deserialization: Transient fields have default values. To restore them properly, implement a private void readObject(ObjectInputStream in) method that calls in.defaultReadObject() first, then manually restores transient fields.", code:`class User implements Serializable {\n    String name;\n    transient String password;  // NOT serialized\n    transient Logger log;      // NOT serialized (not Serializable)\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"transient fields get default values after deserialization (null, 0, false). Use for: passwords, connections, threads, non-serializable objects. Static fields are also not serialized (regardless of transient)." },
      { id:"io5", question:"What is the difference between Serializable and Externalizable?", answer:"Both interfaces support object serialization, but they differ significantly in how much control the developer has and how the serialization is performed.\n\nSerializable (java.io.Serializable): A marker interface with no methods. When a class implements Serializable, the JVM handles serialization automatically using reflection — it discovers all non-transient, non-static fields and serializes them by name and value. This is zero-configuration: implement the interface, add serialVersionUID, and you're done. The JVM also handles deserialization automatically. Drawbacks: (1) Uses reflection — slower than manual serialization, (2) Serializes all non-transient fields — you can't selectively skip fields without marking them transient, (3) The serialized format includes field names and type metadata — larger output, (4) No control over the serialization format or order.\n\nExternalizable (java.io.Externalizable): Extends Serializable and requires two methods: writeExternal(ObjectOutput out) and readExternal(ObjectInput in). The developer has complete control over what and how fields are serialized — you explicitly write each field in writeExternal() and read them back in the same order in readExternal(). Advantages: (1) No reflection — faster than Serializable, (2) Selective serialization — you choose exactly which fields to include, (3) Custom format — you can write data in any format (binary, compressed, encrypted), (4) Smaller output — no field name/type metadata overhead, (5) More secure — you can encrypt sensitive fields. Drawbacks: (1) More code to write and maintain, (2) Must have a public no-arg constructor (the JVM creates an instance using it, then calls readExternal()), (3) If you add/remove fields, you must update both methods manually.\n\nWhen to use which: Use Serializable for simple cases where convenience matters more than performance. Use Externalizable when: you need maximum performance, you want to control the serialized format, you're serializing large objects over a network, or you need to encrypt/compress the data.", code:`class Emp implements Externalizable {\n    String name; int id;\n    public void writeExternal(ObjectOutput out) throws IOException {\n        out.writeUTF(name); out.writeInt(id); // custom write\n    }\n    public void readExternal(ObjectInput in) throws IOException {\n        name=in.readUTF(); id=in.readInt(); // custom read\n    }\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Serializable: zero-config, reflection-based, all non-transient fields. Externalizable: must implement readExternal/writeExternal, no-arg constructor required, selective serialization, better performance." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "memory",
    title: "Memory & JVM",
    icon: "🧠",
    questions: [
      { id:"mem1", question:"How is memory divided in JVM?", answer:"The JVM divides its runtime memory into several distinct areas, each serving a specific purpose. Understanding this division is essential for debugging memory issues and tuning performance.\n\n1. Heap (shared across all threads): The largest memory area, where all objects and arrays are allocated. The heap is managed by the garbage collector and is divided into generations for efficient GC: Young Generation (Eden space + two Survivor spaces S0/S1) — where new objects are allocated; Old Generation (Tenured) — where long-lived objects are promoted after surviving multiple GC cycles; MetaSpace (Java 8+, replaced PermGen) — stores class metadata. When the heap is full, the JVM throws OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space. Heap size is controlled by -Xms (initial) and -Xmx (maximum) flags.\n\n2. Stack (per thread): Each thread has its own stack that stores method frames. Each frame contains: local variable array (method parameters and local variables), operand stack (for JVM calculations), frame data (return address, exception handler reference). Primitive values and object references are stored on the stack; the objects themselves live on the heap. Stack size is controlled by -Xss flag. When the stack overflows (deep recursion), the JVM throws StackOverflowError.\n\n3. Method Area / MetaSpace (shared): Stores class-level information: class structure (fields, methods, constructors), method bytecode, runtime constant pool, static variables, JIT compiler data. Before Java 8, this was called PermGen (Permanent Generation) with a fixed size — it often caused OutOfMemoryError: PermGen space. Since Java 8, MetaSpace uses native memory (off-heap) and grows automatically, eliminating the PermGen problem.\n\n4. Program Counter (PC) Register (per thread): Stores the address of the currently executing JVM instruction. For native methods, the PC is undefined. This is the only memory area that doesn't throw OutOfMemoryError.\n\n5. Native Method Stack (per thread): Similar to the Java stack but for native (C/C++) methods called via JNI. Some JVMs combine this with the Java stack.", code:`// JVM Memory Layout:\n// ┌─────────────────────────────────┐\n// │           HEAP                   │\n// │  Young Gen: Eden + S0 + S1      │\n// │  Old Gen (Tenured)              │\n// │  MetaSpace (Java 8+)            │\n// ├─────────────────────────────────┤\n// │           STACK (per thread)     │\n// │  Local vars, operands, frames   │\n// ├─────────────────────────────────┤\n// │     Method Area / MetaSpace      │\n// │  Class info, constants, statics  │\n// └─────────────────────────────────┘`, codeLanguage:"plaintext", explanation:"Heap: all objects, shared across threads. GC manages heap. Stack: per-thread, method frames, local variables. Method Area: class metadata, static vars, constants (MetaSpace in Java 8+). PC Register: current instruction address. Native Stack: for native methods." },
      { id:"mem2", question:"What is garbage collection in Java?", answer:"Garbage Collection (GC) is Java's automatic memory management system that reclaims memory occupied by objects that are no longer reachable from any live thread. The programmer never needs to explicitly free memory (unlike C/C++ where malloc/free is manual) — the GC automatically identifies and deletes unreachable objects, preventing memory leaks and use-after-free bugs.\n\nHow GC works: The JVM uses a reachability analysis algorithm. Starting from GC Roots (local variables in stack frames, static references, JNI references, active thread objects), the GC traces the object graph — any object reachable from a GC Root through a chain of references is 'live' and must be kept. Any object NOT reachable from any GC Root is 'garbage' and can be collected.\n\nGenerational GC (HotSpot JVM): The HotSpot JVM divides the heap into generations based on the empirical observation that most objects are short-lived (die young). This allows the GC to focus on the young generation frequently (fast, small pauses) and the old generation less frequently (slower, larger pauses).\n- Young Generation: New objects are allocated in Eden. When Eden fills up, a Minor GC runs: live objects are copied to a Survivor space (S0 or S1), and dead objects are discarded. Objects that survive multiple Minor GCs (default threshold: 8) are promoted to the Old Generation.\n- Old Generation: Long-lived objects reside here. When the old generation fills up, a Major GC (or Full GC) runs — this is slower because it scans the entire heap.\n\nGC types: (1) Minor GC — collects only the Young Generation, fast (usually <10ms), (2) Major GC — collects the Old Generation, slower, (3) Full GC — collects the entire heap (Young + Old + MetaSpace), longest pause, should be minimized.\n\nSystem.gc(): Calling System.gc() is merely a SUGGESTION to the JVM that now would be a good time to run GC — the JVM is free to ignore it. Never rely on System.gc() in production code.", code:`Object obj=new Object();\nobj=null; // eligible for GC\nobj=new Object(); // previous object eligible\n// System.gc(); // suggests GC (not guaranteed)\n\n// Object with no references → eligible for GC\n// Island of isolation: circular refs with no external ref`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"GC algorithms: Mark-and-Sweep, Copying, Generational. HotSpot JVM: Generational GC (Young+Old). Young: Eden→Survivor→Old. GC types: Minor (Young), Major (Old), Full (entire heap). System.gc() is a hint, not a command." },
      { id:"mem3", question:"What is the difference between heap and stack memory?", answer:"Heap and stack are two fundamentally different memory areas in the JVM with different purposes, lifecycles, and access patterns.\n\nHeap Memory: A shared memory area (accessible by all threads) where all objects and arrays are allocated at runtime. When you write new Object() or new int[100], the memory comes from the heap. The heap is managed by the garbage collector — objects live until no references point to them, then GC reclaims the memory. Heap is much larger than stack (typically hundreds of MB to GB, controlled by -Xmx). Access is slower than stack because objects can be scattered across the heap (poor cache locality) and allocation requires coordination with GC. When the heap is exhausted, OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space is thrown. Heap memory is not automatically freed when a method returns — objects persist until GC collects them.\n\nStack Memory: A per-thread memory area (each thread has its own independent stack). The stack stores method frames — each method call pushes a frame containing local variables (primitives and object references), the operand stack, and frame data. When a method returns, its frame is popped and the memory is immediately reclaimed — no GC needed. Stack is much smaller than heap (typically 512KB-1MB per thread, controlled by -Xss). Access is very fast because frames are contiguous and managed LIFO. When the stack overflows (too many nested method calls, infinite recursion), StackOverflowError is thrown.\n\nKey differences: (1) Heap is shared; stack is per-thread, (2) Heap stores objects; stack stores primitives and references, (3) Heap is GC-managed; stack is auto-managed (LIFO with method calls), (4) Heap is large; stack is small, (5) Heap access is slower; stack is faster, (6) Heap throws OutOfMemoryError; stack throws StackOverflowError, (7) Objects on heap outlive the method that created them; stack data is freed when the method returns.\n\nThe connection: Object references live on the stack, but the objects they point to live on the heap. Example: void method() { int x=10; Object obj=new Object(); } — x (primitive 10) is on the stack, obj (reference) is on the stack, but the Object instance is on the heap.", code:`void method() {\n    int x=10;            // stack (primitive)\n    Object obj=new Object(); // obj ref on stack, object on heap\n    String s="hello";    // ref on stack, string in pool/heap\n} // x, obj, s popped from stack; heap objects eligible for GC`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Heap: shared, objects, GC managed, larger, slower access, OutOfMemoryError. Stack: per-thread, primitives+refs, LIFO auto-managed, smaller, faster, StackOverflowError. Stack overflow: deep recursion. Heap overflow: too many objects." },
      { id:"mem4", question:"What makes an object eligible for garbage collection?", answer:"An object becomes eligible for garbage collection when it is no longer reachable from any live thread through any chain of references. The GC uses reachability analysis — if no path exists from a GC Root to the object, the object is unreachable and can be collected.\n\nWays an object becomes eligible:\n1. Nullifying references: Setting the only reference to null. Object obj = new Object(); obj = null; — the Object is now unreachable and eligible for GC.\n2. Reassigning references: Pointing the reference to a different object. Object obj = new Object(); obj = new Object(); — the first Object is now unreachable (the reference now points to the second Object).\n3. Objects created inside methods: When a method returns, all its local variables (including references to objects) are popped from the stack. If no other reference exists to those objects, they become eligible. Example: void method() { Object obj = new Object(); } — after method() returns, obj is gone from the stack, and the Object is eligible.\n4. Island of Isolation: A group of objects that reference each other but have no external references from any live thread. Even though they reference each other (forming a cycle), they are collectively unreachable and all eligible. Example: Node n1=new Node(); Node n2=new Node(); n1.next=n2; n2.next=n1; n1=null; n2=null; — both nodes form an isolated island with no external references.\n\nImportant notes: (1) The JVM does NOT guarantee when GC will run or which objects will be collected — GC is non-deterministic. An eligible object may remain in memory until the JVM decides to run GC. (2) Calling System.gc() does NOT force immediate collection — it's a hint. (3) The finalize() method (deprecated since Java 9) was called once by the GC before collecting an object, but it was unreliable and slow — never use it. (4) An object can 'resurrect' itself from GC by creating a new reference to itself inside finalize(), but this is a severe anti-pattern.", code:`Object a=new Object();\nObject b=new Object();\na=b; // first object eligible\na=null; b=null; // both eligible\n\n// Island of isolation\nclass Node { Node next; }\nNode n1=new Node(); Node n2=new Node();\nn1.next=n2; n2.next=n1;\nn1=null; n2=null; // both eligible (island)`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Eligibility: no reference from any live thread, null reference, reassigning reference, island of isolation (circular refs with no external ref). finalize() called once before GC (deprecated). Object.clone() and GC: no direct relation." },
      { id:"mem5", question:"What are the different garbage collectors in JVM?", answer:"The HotSpot JVM offers several garbage collector implementations, each optimized for different use cases — throughput vs. latency vs. memory footprint. You select the GC using JVM flags.\n\n1. Serial GC (-XX:+UseSerialGC): Single-threaded collector that stops all application threads (stop-the-world) during GC. Simple and efficient for small heaps (<~256MB) and single-threaded applications. Not suitable for server applications. Uses mark-sweep-compact for old generation.\n\n2. Parallel GC (-XX:+UseParallelGC): The default in Java 8. Uses multiple threads for GC (as many as CPU cores) to maximize throughput. Application threads are paused during GC (stop-the-world), but the pause is shorter than Serial because work is parallelized. Best for batch processing, scientific computing, and applications where throughput matters more than pause time. Controlled by -XX:ParallelGCThreads.\n\n3. CMS (Concurrent Mark-Sweep) GC (-XX:+UseConcMarkSweepGC, deprecated Java 9, removed Java 14): Attempted to minimize pause times by doing most GC work concurrently with application threads. Used mark-sweep (no compaction) which could lead to fragmentation over time. Had two short stop-the-world pauses (initial mark, remark). Deprecated because it was complex, had fragmentation issues, and G1 was better.\n\n4. G1 (Garbage First) GC (-XX:+UseG1GC, default since Java 9): Divides the heap into equal-sized regions (typically 1-32MB) instead of fixed generations. Regions can be Eden, Survivor, Old, or Humongous (for large objects). G1 prioritizes collecting regions with the most garbage (garbage-first), which maximizes memory reclaimed per unit of GC time. Provides predictable pause times (set target with -XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=200). Performs compaction during collection, avoiding fragmentation. Best for heaps >4GB and applications that need balanced throughput and latency.\n\n5. ZGC (-XX:+UseZGC, production-ready Java 15): Ultra-low latency collector with pause times under 1ms (typically 0.1ms) regardless of heap size. Does almost all work concurrently with the application. Uses colored pointers and load barriers for concurrent object movement. Supports heaps from 8MB to 16TB. Best for applications requiring sub-millisecond pauses (financial trading, real-time systems).\n\n6. Shenandoah GC (-XX:+UseShenandoahGC, production-ready Java 15): Similar goals to ZGC — concurrent compaction with low pause times. Uses Brooks pointers for concurrent object movement. Pauses are independent of heap size. Good alternative to ZGC, especially on OpenJDK builds that include it.", code:`// JVM flags:\n-XX:+UseSerialGC      // single-thread, small apps\n-XX:+UseParallelGC    // throughput-focused\n-XX:+UseG1GC          // balanced (default Java 9+)\n-XX:+UseZGC           // low latency (Java 11+)\n-XX:+UseShenandoahGC  // low pause (Java 12+)`, codeLanguage:"shell", explanation:"Serial: simple, stop-the-world. Parallel: multiple GC threads, best throughput. G1: region-based, balanced pause/throughput, default. ZGC: concurrent, <1ms pause. Shenandoah: concurrent compaction. Choose based on: heap size, pause requirements, throughput needs." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "streams-api",
    title: "Java 8 Stream API",
    icon: "🌊",
    questions: [
      { id:"st1", question:"What is the Stream API?", answer:"The Stream API, introduced in Java 8, is a declarative and functional-style API for processing sequences of elements. A Stream is NOT a data structure — it's a view of a data source (collection, array, I/O channel) that supports aggregate operations (filter, map, reduce, collect) performed in a pipeline. Streams enable concise, readable, and potentially parallel data processing without explicit loops or mutable state.\n\nKey characteristics: (1) Lazy evaluation: Intermediate operations (filter, map, sorted) are not executed until a terminal operation (collect, forEach) is invoked. This allows the JVM to optimize the pipeline — e.g., filter-map-collect can be fused into a single pass over the data. (2) Non-interfering: Stream operations don't modify the underlying data source — they produce new results. (3) Consumable once: A stream can be traversed only once. After a terminal operation executes, the stream is consumed and cannot be reused. (4) Possibly parallel: Calling parallelStream() or .parallel() enables automatic parallel processing using the ForkJoinPool — no manual thread management needed. (5) Internal iteration: Unlike external iteration (for-each, iterators), streams use internal iteration — the library controls the iteration, enabling optimizations like short-circuiting and fusion.\n\nStream pipeline structure: A stream pipeline consists of: (a) A source (collection.stream(), Arrays.stream(), Stream.of(), Stream.generate()), (b) Zero or more intermediate operations (lazy, return a new Stream), (c) One terminal operation (triggers execution, produces a result or side-effect).\n\nCommon intermediate operations: filter(Predicate) — keep matching elements, map(Function) — transform each element, flatMap(Function) — transform + flatten, sorted() — sort elements, distinct() — remove duplicates, limit(n) — take first n elements, skip(n) — skip first n elements, peek(Consumer) — inspect without consuming.\n\nCommon terminal operations: collect(Collector) — accumulate into a collection, forEach(Consumer) — perform action on each, reduce(BinaryOperator) — combine into one, count() — count elements, findFirst/findAny — find an element, anyMatch/allMatch/noneMatch — test elements.", code:`List<String> names=List.of("Alice","Bob","Charlie","Anna");\nList<String> result=names.stream()\n    .filter(n -> n.startsWith("A"))\n    .map(String::toUpperCase)\n    .sorted()\n    .collect(Collectors.toList());\n// [ALICE, ANNA]`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Stream: pipeline of operations. Lazy: intermediate ops execute only when terminal op called. Operations: intermediate (filter, map, sorted, distinct, limit) + terminal (collect, forEach, reduce, count, findFirst). Can be parallel with .parallelStream()." },
      { id:"st2", question:"What is the difference between map() and flatMap()?", answer:"map() and flatMap() are both intermediate operations that transform stream elements, but they differ in how many output elements each input produces and whether the result is flattened.\n\nmap(Function<T, R>): Transforms each element one-to-one. For every input element, map produces exactly one output element. The mapping function takes T and returns R. The resulting stream has the same number of elements as the input stream (unless exceptions occur). Example: stream.map(String::toUpperCase) — each String becomes its uppercase version. One String in, one String out. Use map when each element maps to a single result — simple transformations like type conversion, field extraction, arithmetic operations.\n\nflatMap(Function<T, Stream<R>>): Transforms each element one-to-many AND flattens the results. The mapping function takes T and returns a Stream<R> (not just R). Each input element can produce zero, one, or many output elements. The streams returned by the mapping function are 'flattened' — their elements are merged into a single continuous stream. Without flatMap, mapping to a Stream would give you Stream<Stream<R>>, which is nested and unusable. flatMap eliminates the nesting. Example: stream.flatMap(s -> Arrays.stream(s.split(''))) — each String becomes a Stream of its individual characters, and all character streams are flattened into a single Stream<Character>.\n\nKey difference: map produces a 1:1 mapping (Stream<R> from Stream<T>), flatMap produces a 1:N mapping with flattening (Stream<R> from Stream<Stream<R>>). Use map for simple one-to-one transformations. Use flatMap when: (1) Each element maps to multiple values (splitting strings, expanding nested collections), (2) You need to flatten nested structures (List<List<T>> → Stream<T>), (3) You're working with Optional (Optional.flatMap chains operations that may return empty Optionals).", code:`// map: 1-to-1\nList<String> upper=names.stream()\n    .map(String::toUpperCase)\n    .collect(Collectors.toList());\n\n// flatMap: 1-to-N + flatten\nList<List<String>> nested=List.of(\n    List.of("a","b"), List.of("c","d"));\nList<String> flat=nested.stream()\n    .flatMap(Collection::stream)\n    .collect(Collectors.toList()); // [a,b,c,d]`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"map: each element→one element. Function<T,R>. flatMap: each element→stream of elements, all flattened. Function<T,Stream<R>>. Use map for simple transform, flatMap when each element maps to multiple values (nested collections, splitting strings)." },
      { id:"st3", question:"What is the difference between findFirst() and findAny()?", answer:"Both findFirst() and findAny() are short-circuiting terminal operations that return an Optional containing an element from the stream, but they differ in ordering guarantees and performance characteristics.\n\nfindFirst(): Returns an Optional containing the FIRST element in the encounter order of the stream, or an empty Optional if the stream is empty. The encounter order is the order defined by the source (e.g., List maintains insertion order, HashSet has no defined order). findFirst() is deterministic — for the same source, it always returns the same element. In a sequential stream, findFirst() simply returns the first element. In a parallel stream, findFirst() must find the first element in encounter order, which may require waiting for other threads to complete their portions — this can reduce the performance benefit of parallelism. Use findFirst() when the order matters (e.g., getting the first match in a sorted list, finding the earliest date).\n\nfindAny(): Returns an Optional containing ANY element from the stream, or an empty Optional if the stream is empty. The JVM is free to return any element — there is no guarantee which one. In a sequential stream, findAny() typically returns the first element (same as findFirst), but this is not guaranteed. In a parallel stream, findAny() can return whichever element is found first by any thread — it doesn't need to wait for the encounter-order first element. This makes findAny() significantly faster in parallel streams because it can short-circuit as soon as any thread finds a match. Use findAny() when you just need any matching element and don't care which one (e.g., checking if any element exists, picking a random valid item).\n\nBoth return Optional<T> — always check with isPresent() or use orElse/orElseThrow before accessing the value. Both are short-circuiting — they stop processing as soon as a result is found (they don't process the entire stream).", code:`List<String> list=List.of("A","B","C","D");\nlist.stream().findFirst(); // Optional[A] — always first\nlist.stream().findAny();   // Optional[A] — any element\nlist.parallelStream().findAny(); // may vary`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"findFirst: deterministic, respects encounter order, slightly slower in parallel. findAny: no order constraint, faster in parallel streams. Both return Optional. Use findFirst when order matters, findAny when any match suffices." },
      { id:"st4", question:"What are the different Collectors?", answer:"Collectors is a utility class in java.util.stream that provides ready-made implementations of the Collector interface for common reduction operations. A Collector accumulates stream elements into a mutable result container, optionally performs a finisher transformation, and supports parallel accumulation via combiner functions. The Collectors class provides factory methods for the most common patterns:\n\nCollection Collectors: toList() — accumulates into an ArrayList, toSet() — accumulates into a HashSet, toUnmodifiableList()/toUnmodifiableSet() (Java 10) — immutable collections, toCollection(Supplier) — accumulates into a specified collection (e.g., LinkedList, TreeSet), toMap(keyMapper, valueMapper) — accumulates into a HashMap (throws on duplicate keys), toMap(keyMapper, valueMapper, mergeFunction) — handles duplicate keys with a merge function, toConcurrentMap() — thread-safe map for parallel streams.\n\nString Collectors: joining() — concatenates elements into a String, joining(delimiter) — concatenates with delimiter, joining(delimiter, prefix, suffix) — full control (e.g., '[A, B, C]').\n\nGrouping Collectors: groupingBy(classifier) — groups elements by a classifier function into Map<K, List<T>> (SQL GROUP BY equivalent), groupingBy(classifier, downstream) — groups and applies a downstream collector to each group (e.g., counting per group), groupingBy(classifier, mapFactory, downstream) — controls the Map implementation, partitioningBy(predicate) — splits into two groups (true/false) into Map<Boolean, List<T>>, partitioningBy(predicate, downstream) — partitions with downstream collector.\n\nStatistical Collectors: counting() — counts elements, summingInt/summingLong/summingDouble(toIntFunction) — sums a numeric property, averagingInt/averagingLong/averagingDouble(toIntFunction) — averages a numeric property, summarizingInt/summarizingLong/summarizingDouble — returns summary statistics (count, sum, min, max, average) in one pass, maxBy/minBy(Comparator) — finds max/min element.\n\nAdvanced Collectors: collectingAndThen(collector, finisher) — applies a transformation after collection, mapping(mapper, downstream) — applies a mapping before downstream collection, flatMapping(mapper, downstream) (Java 9) — flat-maps before downstream, filtering(predicate, downstream) (Java 9) — filters before downstream, teeing(downstream1, downstream2, merger) (Java 12) — applies two collectors and merges results.", code:`// toList, toSet, toMap\nList<String> list=stream.collect(Collectors.toList());\nSet<String> set=stream.collect(Collectors.toSet());\nMap<String,Integer> map=stream.collect(Collectors.toMap(s->s, String::length));\n\n// joining\nString joined=stream.collect(Collectors.joining(", "));\n\n// groupingBy\nMap<Integer,List<String>> byLen=stream.collect(\n    Collectors.groupingBy(String::length));\n\n// partitioningBy (2 groups)\nMap<Boolean,List<String>> byLen5=stream.collect(\n    Collectors.partitioningBy(s -> s.length()>5));\n\n// counting, summingInt, averagingInt\nlong count=stream.collect(Collectors.counting());`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"toList/toSet/toMap: basic collection creation. joining: concatenate strings. groupingBy: SQL GROUP BY equivalent. partitioningBy: boolean key grouping. counting/summing/averaging: statistics. collectingAndThen: post-process. teeing (Java 12): two collectors." },
      { id:"st5", question:"What is the difference between intermediate and terminal operations?", answer:"Stream operations are divided into two categories: intermediate operations (lazy) and terminal operations (eager). Understanding this distinction is essential for writing correct and efficient stream pipelines.\n\nIntermediate Operations: Operations that return a new Stream, allowing them to be chained. They are LAZY — they don't execute any processing when called. Instead, they record the operation and return a new stream that will apply it when the pipeline is triggered. No data is processed, no elements are consumed, and no side effects occur until a terminal operation is invoked. This laziness enables performance optimizations: the JVM can fuse multiple operations into a single pass (e.g., filter-map-collect becomes one loop), and short-circuiting operations can stop early without processing the entire stream. Common intermediate operations: filter(), map(), flatMap(), sorted(), distinct(), limit(), skip(), peek(), takeWhile() (Java 9), dropWhile() (Java 9).\n\nTerminal Operations: Operations that produce a result (a value, a collection, a side-effect) or return void. They are EAGER — when a terminal operation is called, the entire stream pipeline is triggered and executed. The stream source is consumed, all intermediate operations are applied, and the final result is produced. After a terminal operation executes, the stream is consumed and cannot be used again (IllegalStateException on reuse). Common terminal operations: collect(), forEach(), forEachOrdered(), toArray(), reduce(), collect(), min(), max(), count(), findFirst(), findAny(), anyMatch(), allMatch(), noneMatch().\n\nShort-circuiting operations: Some operations can complete without processing the entire stream. Short-circuiting intermediate: limit(), takeWhile() — stop after a condition. Short-circuiting terminal: findFirst(), findAny(), anyMatch(), allMatch(), noneMatch() — return as soon as the answer is known. Short-circuiting is especially valuable for infinite streams (Stream.generate(), Stream.iterate()).\n\nKey rules: (1) A stream pipeline must have exactly one terminal operation — without it, nothing executes, (2) A stream can only be consumed once — calling a terminal operation twice on the same stream throws IllegalStateException, (3) Intermediate operations are for building the pipeline; terminal operations are for executing it.", code:`// Intermediate (lazy — nothing happens until terminal)\nStream<String> s=list.stream()\n    .filter(n -> n.length()>3)  // intermediate\n    .map(String::toUpperCase);   // intermediate\n// Nothing executed yet!\n\n// Terminal (triggers execution)\nList<String> result=s.collect(Collectors.toList()); // now executes`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Intermediate: lazy, short-circuiting possible (limit, takeWhile). Terminal: eager, produces result or side-effect. Only one terminal per stream. Stream is consumed after terminal operation. Short-circuit terminals: findFirst, findAny, anyMatch, allMatch, noneMatch." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "misc",
    title: "Miscellaneous & Advanced",
    icon: "🎓",
    questions: [
      { id:"m1", question:"What is the difference between shallow copy and deep copy?", answer:"Shallow copy and deep copy are two strategies for copying objects, and they differ fundamentally in how they handle nested (referenced) objects.\n\nShallow Copy: Creates a new object and copies all field values from the original. For primitive fields, the actual value is copied. For reference fields (objects, arrays), only the REFERENCE is copied — both the original and the copy point to the SAME nested object. This means changes to the nested object through one reference are visible through the other. In Java, Object.clone() performs a shallow copy by default — it does a field-by-field copy without recursively cloning referenced objects.\n\nDeep Copy: Creates a new object AND recursively copies all objects referenced by its fields. The copy and the original have completely independent copies of all nested objects — no shared references. Changes to any nested object in the copy do not affect the original, and vice versa. Deep copy requires explicit implementation — you must manually clone each nested object, or use serialization/deserialization to create a complete copy.\n\nHow to implement deep copy: (1) Override clone() and manually clone each mutable reference field: protected Object clone() { Person p = (Person) super.clone(); p.addr = (Address) addr.clone(); return p; }, (2) Copy constructor: Person(Person other) { this.name = other.name; this.addr = new Address(other.addr); }, (3) Serialization: serialize the object to bytes and deserialize it back — this creates a completely independent copy of the entire object graph, (4) Deep cloning libraries (Apache Commons SerializationUtils, Kryo).\n\nWhen to use which: Use shallow copy when objects contain only primitives or immutable references (String, Integer). Use deep copy when objects contain mutable references (collections, custom objects) and you need true independence between copies.", code:`// Shallow copy (clone)\nclass Address { String city; }\nclass Person implements Cloneable {\n    String name; Address addr;\n    protected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {\n        return super.clone(); // shallow — addr shared\n    }\n}\n// Deep copy\nprotected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {\n    Person p=(Person)super.clone();\n    p.addr=new Address(); // new Address object\n    p.addr.city=this.addr.city; // copy values\n    return p;\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Shallow: clone() default behavior, nested objects shared. Deep: must manually clone nested objects. Deep copy alternatives: copy constructor, serialization, deep cloning libraries. Changes to shared objects affect both copies in shallow." },
      { id:"m2", question:"What is the Cloneable interface?", answer:"The Cloneable interface is a marker interface in java.lang that indicates a class allows field-by-field copying via the Object.clone() method. It has no methods — its sole purpose is to signal to the JVM that calling clone() on instances of this class should be allowed.\n\nHow cloning works: Object.clone() is a protected method that performs a shallow field-by-field copy. If a class doesn't implement Cloneable, calling super.clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException. If it does implement Cloneable, super.clone() creates a new instance and copies each field's value (bitwise copy for primitives, reference copy for objects).\n\nThe Cloneable contract is considered broken by many experts (Joshua Bloch, Effective Java): (1) It's a marker interface with no methods — the actual clone() method is in Object, not Cloneable, which is confusing, (2) clone() is protected — you must override it as public to make it accessible, (3) It performs shallow copy by default — for mutable fields, you must manually implement deep copy logic, (4) It doesn't call constructors — the new object is created without any constructor, which can break invariants, (5) The Cloneable interface doesn't declare clone() — the compiler doesn't enforce that you override it correctly.\n\nBest practice: Prefer copy constructors or factory methods over Cloneable. A copy constructor is explicit, type-safe, doesn't require casting, handles deep copy naturally, and works with final fields. Example: Student(Student other) { this.name = other.name; } is cleaner than implementing Cloneable and overriding clone().", code:`class Student implements Cloneable {\n    String name;\n    protected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {\n        return super.clone(); // shallow copy\n    }\n}\nStudent s1=new Student();\nStudent s2=(Student)s1.clone();`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Cloneable: marker interface (no methods). Object.clone(): protected, shallow copy by default. Must override clone() as public for external use. Cloneable is considered broken by many—prefer copy constructor or factory method." },
      { id:"m3", question:"What is the difference between Comparator nullsFirst and nullsLast?", answer:"nullsFirst and nullsLast are static methods in the Comparator class (Java 8+) that provide null-safe sorting strategies. Without them, sorting a collection containing null elements throws NullPointerException because comparing null with any value using compareTo() fails.\n\nComparator.nullsFirst(Comparator): Null elements are placed BEFORE all non-null elements in the sorted result. Non-null elements are sorted among themselves using the provided comparator. Example: list with [B, null, A, null, C] sorted with nullsFirst(naturalOrder()) gives [null, null, A, B, C]. Use when you want nulls at the beginning — analogous to how some databases treat NULL as the smallest value.\n\nComparator.nullsLast(Comparator): Null elements are placed AFTER all non-null elements in the sorted result. Non-null elements are sorted among themselves using the provided comparator. Example: list with [B, null, A, null, C] sorted with nullsLast(naturalOrder()) gives [A, B, C, null, null]. Use when you want nulls at the end — analogous to how some databases treat NULL as the largest value.\n\nThe comparator argument: Both methods take a Comparator that defines the ordering of the non-null elements. You can pass Comparator.naturalOrder() for default ordering, Comparator.reverseOrder() for descending, or any custom comparator. If you pass null as the comparator, all non-null elements are treated as equal (no ordering among them), and only null vs non-null ordering is applied.\n\nChaining: You can combine with other comparators: list.sort(Comparator.comparing(Person::getName, Comparator.nullsLast(String.CASE_INSENSITIVE_ORDER)));", code:`List<String> list=Arrays.asList("B",null,"A",null,"C");\nlist.sort(Comparator.nullsFirst(Comparator.naturalOrder()));\n// [null, null, A, B, C]\nlist.sort(Comparator.nullsLast(Comparator.naturalOrder()));\n// [A, B, C, null, null]`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"nullsFirst: nulls sorted first, then non-null by specified comparator. nullsLast: non-null sorted first, then nulls. Without these, sorting with nulls throws NPE. Useful for database-like sorting." },
      { id:"m4", question:"What is the Optional class?", answer:"Optional<T> is a container object introduced in Java 8 that may or may not contain a non-null value. It's designed to make the presence or absence of a value explicit in the API, eliminating the need for null checks and reducing NullPointerException occurrences. Optional forces the caller to acknowledge that a value might be absent and handle both cases.\n\nCreating Optionals: Optional.of(value) — wraps a non-null value; throws NPE if value is null. Optional.ofNullable(value) — wraps a value that may be null; returns empty Optional if null. Optional.empty() — returns an empty Optional.\n\nChecking and consuming: isPresent() — returns true if a value is present. isEmpty() (Java 11) — returns true if no value. ifPresent(Consumer) — executes the consumer if value is present, does nothing otherwise. ifPresentOrElse(Consumer, Runnable) (Java 9) — executes consumer if present, runnable if empty.\n\nGetting the value: get() — returns the value if present; throws NoSuchElementException if empty (avoid this — it defeats the purpose of Optional). orElse(default) — returns the value if present, otherwise returns the default value. orElseGet(Supplier) — returns the value if present, otherwise invokes the supplier and returns its result (lazy — supplier only called when empty). orElseThrow() (Java 10) — returns the value if present, otherwise throws NoSuchElementException. orElseThrow(Supplier) — returns the value if present, otherwise throws the exception created by the supplier.\n\nTransforming: map(Function) — if present, applies the function and wraps the result; if empty, returns empty. flatMap(Function) — like map but the function must return Optional (prevents Optional<Optional<T>>). filter(Predicate) — if present and matches predicate, returns same Optional; otherwise returns empty.\n\nBest practices: (1) Use Optional ONLY for return types — never for fields, method parameters, or constructor parameters, (2) Never call get() without first checking isPresent() — prefer orElse/orElseGet/orElseThrow, (3) Don't use Optional for optional method arguments — use method overloading instead, (4) Don't use Optional for collections — return empty collection instead of Optional<List>, (5) Use Optional with streams — Optional.stream() (Java 9) converts to a Stream of 0 or 1 elements.", code:`Optional<String> opt=Optional.ofNullable(getName());\n// Check\nif(opt.isPresent()) { }\nopt.ifPresent(s -> System.out.println(s));\n// Get with default\nString name=opt.orElse("Unknown");\nString name2=opt.orElseGet(() -> getDefault());\n// Throw if empty\nString name3=opt.orElseThrow(() -> new RuntimeException());\n// Transform\nOptional<Integer> len=opt.map(String::length);`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"of(): non-null required (NPE if null). ofNullable(): null allowed. isPresent(): has value. ifPresent(): consume if present. orElse/orElseGet/orElseThrow: default values. map/flatMap/filter: transform. Never use Optional for fields or method parameters—only for return types." },
      { id:"m5", question:"What is the difference between varargs and array parameter?", answer:"Varargs (variable-length arguments) and array parameters both allow passing multiple values to a method, but they differ in flexibility and syntax.\n\nVarargs (Type... name): Introduced in Java 5. Allows calling the method with zero or more arguments of the specified type. The compiler automatically creates an array from the supplied arguments at the call site. Syntax: int sum(int... nums) — the caller can write sum(), sum(1), sum(1,2,3), or sum(new int[]{1,2,3}). Internally, nums is an int[] array. Varargs must be the LAST parameter in the method signature — you can have only one varargs parameter per method. Varargs is syntactic sugar — the method body treats the parameter as a normal array.\n\nArray parameter (Type[] name): The traditional approach. The caller must create and pass an array explicitly: int sum(int[] nums) — the caller must write sum(new int[]{1,2,3}) or sum(myArray). No flexibility in argument count — you must pass exactly one array.\n\nKey differences: (1) Varargs allows flexible argument count (0 to many); array requires exactly one array, (2) Varargs is more convenient for callers — no array creation at call site, (3) Varargs creates a new array per call (minor performance overhead for hot paths), (4) Array parameter gives the caller control over the array (can reuse, pre-allocate), (5) Varargs must be the last parameter; arrays can be anywhere, (6) Overloading with varargs can cause ambiguous method calls — the compiler may not know which overload to choose.\n\nBest practice: Use varargs when the method is called with varying numbers of arguments (e.g., String.format, Arrays.asList). Use array when the number of arguments is fixed or when performance is critical (avoiding array allocation per call).", code:`// varargs — flexible number of arguments\nint sum(int... nums) {\n    int total=0;\n    for(int n:nums) total+=n;\n    return total;\n}\nsum();        // 0\nsum(1,2,3);   // 6\nsum(new int[]{1,2,3}); // also works\n\n// Must be last parameter\nvoid print(String format, Object... args) { }`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"varargs: Type... name, must be last parameter, only one per method, compiler creates array. Overloading with varargs can be ambiguous. Prefer explicit array when arg count is known/fixed. Varargs creates array each call (minor overhead)." },
      { id:"m6", question:"What is the difference between class loader types?", answer:"Java uses a hierarchy of class loaders to load classes at runtime, following the Parent Delegation Model. Each class loader delegates class loading to its parent before attempting to load the class itself. This ensures that core Java classes are always loaded by the trusted bootstrap loader, preventing malicious code from overriding them.\n\n1. Bootstrap Class Loader: The root class loader, implemented in C++ (not a Java class). Loads the JDK's most fundamental classes from rt.jar (Java 8) or the java.base module (Java 9+). These include java.lang.Object, java.lang.String, java.util.Collection, and all other core API classes. When you call String.class.getClassLoader(), it returns null — indicating the class was loaded by the bootstrap loader (which isn't a Java object).\n\n2. Platform Class Loader (Java 9+, formerly Extension Class Loader): Loads classes from JDK extension modules (Java 9+) or the ext/lib directory (Java 8). These include security extensions, crypto providers, and other JDK-supplied extensions. It's implemented as jdk.internal.loader.ClassLoaders$PlatformClassLoader. Before Java 9, it was called the Extension Class Loader and loaded from $JAVA_HOME/lib/ext.\n\n3. Application Class Loader (also called System Class Loader): Loads classes from the application's classpath — your application's classes, third-party libraries, and any JARs specified with -classpath or -cp. It's implemented as jdk.internal.loader.ClassLoaders$AppClassLoader. When you call MyClass.class.getClassLoader(), it typically returns this loader.\n\nParent Delegation Model: When a class loader receives a request to load a class, it first delegates to its parent. If the parent can load the class (already loaded or found in its path), the parent's definition is used. Only if the parent fails does the child loader attempt to load the class itself. This prevents: (1) Overriding core classes (a custom java.lang.String would be rejected), (2) Duplicate class loading (same class loaded once by the highest loader that can find it).\n\nCustom Class Loaders: You can create your own by extending ClassLoader. Use cases: hot deployment (reload classes without restarting), plugin systems, isolation (different versions of same library), dynamic code generation.", code:`// Class loader hierarchy (parent delegation):\n// Bootstrap (rt.jar, java.lang.*)\n//   ↑ Platform (jdk/ext dirs, Java 9+ modules)\n//     ↑ Application (classpath, your classes)\n\n// Check class loader\nString.class.getClassLoader(); // null (bootstrap)\nMyClass.class.getClassLoader(); // AppClassLoader`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Parent Delegation: child asks parent first, prevents overriding core classes. Bootstrap: C++ implemented, loads JDK internals. Platform: JDK extensions. Application: user classpath. Custom: can be created for plugins, hot-deploy." },
      { id:"m7", question:"What is the difference between shallow comparison and deep comparison?", answer:"Shallow and deep comparison refer to different levels of equality checking for objects and arrays.\n\nShallow Comparison (==): Compares references (memory addresses), not content. Two variables are == only if they point to the exact same object in memory. For primitives, == compares values directly. For objects, == checks if both references point to the same heap object. Example: String[] a1={'A','B'}; String[] a2={'A','B'}; — a1 == a2 is false because they are different array objects, even though they contain the same elements.\n\nDeep Comparison (.equals() and utility methods): Compares the actual content of objects. The .equals() method, when properly overridden, compares field-by-field. For String and wrapper classes (Integer, Double, etc.), equals() compares values. However, for arrays, equals() is the same as == — it compares references, not elements! This is because arrays don't override Object.equals().\n\nArray comparison utilities in java.util.Arrays: Arrays.equals(a1, a2) — performs element-by-element comparison for 1D arrays. It checks each pair of elements using their equals() method. Works for primitive arrays and object arrays. Arrays.deepEquals(a1, a2) — performs recursive deep comparison for nested arrays (2D, 3D, etc.). It handles arrays of arrays by recursively comparing inner arrays element-by-element. Use deepEquals when comparing multidimensional arrays.\n\nGuidelines: For String/wrappers: use equals(). For 1D arrays: use Arrays.equals(). For nested arrays: use Arrays.deepEquals(). For custom objects: override equals() to compare significant fields. Never use == for content comparison of objects or arrays.", code:`String[] a1={"A","B"}; String[] a2={"A","B"};\na1==a2;                  // false (different arrays)\na1.equals(a2);          // false (array equals=ref)\nArrays.equals(a1,a2);   // true (element-by-element)\n\nint[][] d1={{1,2},{3}}; int[][] d2={{1,2},{3}};\nArrays.equals(d1,d2);   // false (nested arrays)\nArrays.deepEquals(d1,d2); // true (deep comparison)`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"==: reference comparison. .equals(): content for String/wrappers, reference for arrays. Arrays.equals(): element-by-element for 1D. Arrays.deepEquals(): recursive for nested arrays. Always use appropriate comparison method." },
      { id:"m8", question:"What are Java records? (Java 14+)", answer:"Records are a special kind of class introduced in Java 14 (preview) and finalized in Java 16, designed specifically for immutable data carriers. They dramatically reduce boilerplate for classes that primarily hold data — the compiler auto-generates constructors, accessor methods, equals(), hashCode(), and toString() based on the record's components (fields).\n\nWhat records auto-generate: (1) A canonical constructor that accepts all components as parameters and assigns them, (2) Accessor methods named after the component (e.g., x() not getX()), (3) equals() based on all components — two records are equal if all components are equal, (4) hashCode() based on all components — consistent with equals(), (5) toString() including all component names and values.\n\nRecord restrictions: (1) Records are implicitly final — cannot be extended, (2) Cannot extend other classes (already extends java.lang.Record), (3) Cannot declare instance fields (only the components), (4) Instance fields (components) are implicitly final — records are immutable, (5) Cannot be abstract.\n\nWhat you CAN add: (1) Compact constructor for validation: public Employee { if(salary<0) throw new IllegalArgumentException(); } — note: no parameter list, the constructor implicitly has all components as parameters. (2) Static fields and methods, (3) Instance methods, (4) Additional constructors (must delegate to the canonical constructor), (5) Implement interfaces.\n\nUse cases: DTOs (Data Transfer Objects), value objects, method return types with multiple values, configuration objects, event objects. Records are perfect anywhere you'd create a class just to hold data with getters, equals, hashCode, and toString.", code:`record Point(int x, int y) { }\nrecord Employee(String name, int id, double salary) {\n    // Compact constructor for validation\n    public Employee {\n        if(salary<0) throw new IllegalArgumentException();\n    }\n}\nPoint p=new Point(3,4);\np.x(); // 3 (not getX())\np.y(); // 4`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Records: final, immutable, extends java.lang.Record. Auto-generated: constructor, accessor methods (x(), not getX()), equals, hashCode, toString. Can add: compact constructors, static methods/fields, instance methods. Cannot: extend other classes, declare instance fields. Perfect for DTOs, value objects." },
      { id:"m9", question:"What is the difference between StringBuilder and StringBuffer capacity?", answer:"Both StringBuilder and StringBuffer use the same internal mechanism for managing character storage capacity, but they differ in thread safety.\n\nCapacity management: Both start with a default capacity of 16 characters (if no initial size is specified). When appending characters exceeds the current capacity, the buffer automatically grows using the formula: newCapacity = (oldCapacity * 2) + 2. This doubling strategy ensures amortized O(1) append operations. You can specify an initial capacity: new StringBuilder(100) — useful when you know the approximate final size to avoid repeated resizing.\n\nKey methods: capacity() — returns current buffer capacity (may be larger than length), length() — returns number of characters stored, ensureCapacity(min) — guarantees the capacity is at least the specified minimum (prevents multiple resizes if you know you'll add many characters), trimToSize() — reduces capacity to match the current length, releasing unused memory.\n\nStringBuilder vs StringBuffer: (1) StringBuilder is NOT thread-safe (no synchronization) — faster, use in single-threaded contexts, (2) StringBuffer IS thread-safe (all methods synchronized) — slower, use when multiple threads access the same instance, (3) Both have the same API and capacity behavior, (4) StringBuilder was introduced in Java 5 as the unsynchronized replacement for StringBuffer, (5) In practice, almost always use StringBuilder — string building is rarely shared across threads.\n\nPerformance tip: If you know the approximate final size, pre-allocate with new StringBuilder(estimatedSize) — this avoids all resizing overhead. For example, when building a CSV string from 1000 rows, estimate the size and create the builder with that capacity.", code:`StringBuilder sb=new StringBuilder();     // capacity 16\nStringBuilder sb2=new StringBuilder(100); // capacity 100\nsb.append("A very long string...");\nsb.capacity(); // auto-expanded\nsb.ensureCapacity(500); // ensure minimum capacity\nsb.trimToSize(); // reduce to actual size`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Initial capacity: 16 (default) or specified. Growth: (old*2)+2 automatically. ensureCapacity(): pre-allocate to avoid repeated expansion. trimToSize(): release unused memory. StringBuilder preferred for single-thread, StringBuffer for multi-thread." },
      { id:"m10", question:"What are sealed classes? (Java 17)", answer:"Sealed classes, introduced as a preview in Java 15 and finalized in Java 17, allow developers to restrict which classes can extend or implement them. Unlike final classes (which allow no subclasses) or open classes (which allow unlimited subclasses), sealed classes provide a middle ground — they explicitly list the permitted subclasses using the permits clause.\n\nDeclaration syntax: sealed class Shape permits Circle, Rectangle { ... } — only Circle and Rectangle can extend Shape. No other class can extend it, even within the same package. The permits clause lists all allowed subclasses by name.\n\nPermitted subclass modifiers: Every permitted subclass must declare one of three modifiers: (1) final — cannot be further extended (the most restrictive), (2) sealed — can only be extended by its own permitted subclasses (continues the restriction chain), (3) non-sealed — opens the hierarchy — any class can extend it (breaks the sealing). The compiler ensures every permitted subclass has exactly one of these modifiers.\n\nSealed interfaces: Interfaces can also be sealed: sealed interface Expression permits Literal, Addition, Multiplication { ... }. Permitted implementations can be classes (must implement the interface) or interfaces (can be sealed themselves).\n\nWhy sealed classes matter: (1) Exhaustive pattern matching: The compiler knows all possible subclasses, so it can verify that switch expressions and pattern matching cover all cases — if you add a new permitted subclass, the compiler flags incomplete switches, (2) Controlled hierarchy: Like enums but for class hierarchies — you get the benefits of a known, finite set of types without being limited to simple enum values, (3) Domain modeling: Perfect for modeling closed domains where the set of types is known and fixed (AST nodes, expression types, payment method types), (4) Security: Prevents unauthorized extension of your API.\n\nSealed classes + pattern matching (Java 21): switch (shape) { case Circle c -> ...; case Rectangle r -> ...; // compiler knows this is exhaustive — no default needed }", code:`sealed class Shape permits Circle, Rectangle {\n    abstract double area();\n}\nfinal class Circle extends Shape {\n    double r;\n    double area() { return Math.PI*r*r; }\n}\nnon-sealed class Rectangle extends Shape {\n    double w, h;\n    double area() { return w*h; }\n}\n// Only Circle and Rectangle can extend Shape`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"sealed: restricts subclasses. permits: lists allowed subclasses. Subclass must be: final, sealed, or non-sealed. Benefits: exhaustive pattern matching, controlled hierarchy. Works with interfaces too. Enables compiler to check completeness in switch expressions." },
      { id:"m11", question:"What is the difference between Stack and Queue?", answer:"Stack and Queue are two fundamental data structures with opposite ordering principles, and Java provides several implementations for each.\n\nStack (LIFO — Last In, First Out): The last element added is the first one removed. Think of a stack of plates — you add to the top and remove from the top. Java's legacy Stack class extends Vector (synchronized, slow) — it's considered obsolete. The modern replacement is using Deque (ArrayDeque) as a stack: Deque<String> stack = new ArrayDeque<>(); stack.push('A'); stack.pop(); — push/pop/peek operations. ArrayDeque is faster than Stack because it's not synchronized.\n\nQueue (FIFO — First In, First Out): The first element added is the first one removed. Think of a line at a store — first person in line is served first. Java's Queue interface is implemented by LinkedList (also implements List), ArrayDeque (also implements Deque), and PriorityQueue. Operations: offer(E) adds to the tail, poll() removes from the head, peek() views the head without removing.\n\nPriorityQueue: A specialized queue where elements are ordered by priority (natural ordering or a Comparator), not by insertion order. The element with the smallest value (or highest priority per comparator) is at the head. Internally uses a min-heap data structure. Offer/poll are O(log n). Use for: task scheduling, Dijkstra's algorithm, Huffman coding, any scenario where you need to always process the 'most important' element next.\n\nDeque (Double-Ended Queue): Supports insertion and removal at both ends. Can be used as both a Stack (push/pop from one end) and a Queue (offer at tail, poll from head). ArrayDeque is the best implementation — it's faster than LinkedList for both stack and queue operations because it uses a resizable array (better cache locality) instead of linked nodes.\n\nBest practice: Never use the legacy Stack class. Use ArrayDeque for both stack and queue operations. Use PriorityQueue when you need priority ordering.", code:`// Stack (LIFO)\nDeque<String> stack=new ArrayDeque<>();\nstack.push("A"); stack.push("B");\nstack.pop(); // "B" (last in)\n\n// Queue (FIFO)\nQueue<String> queue=new LinkedList<>();\nqueue.offer("A"); queue.offer("B");\nqueue.poll(); // "A" (first in)\n\n// PriorityQueue — ordered by priority\nPriorityQueue<Integer> pq=new PriorityQueue<>();\npq.offer(3); pq.offer(1); pq.offer(2);\npq.poll(); // 1 (smallest first)`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Stack: push/pop/peek, LIFO. Queue: offer/poll/peek, FIFO. Deque: both ends. PriorityQueue: ordered by natural/comparator. Prefer ArrayDeque over Stack (Stack extends Vector=synchronized overhead). ArrayDeque also better than LinkedList for queue/deque." },
      { id:"m12", question:"What is the difference between Enumeration and Iterator?", answer:"Enumeration and Iterator are both interfaces for traversing collections, but Iterator is the modern replacement for Enumeration with more features and safer behavior.\n\nEnumeration (java.util.Enumeration): The original iteration interface from Java 1.0, designed for legacy collection classes (Vector, Hashtable). Methods: hasMoreElements() — checks if more elements exist, nextElement() — returns the next element as Object. Limitations: (1) Read-only — cannot remove elements during iteration, (2) Not fail-fast — if the collection is modified during iteration, Enumeration continues without error (may produce inconsistent results), (3) No generic type support — returns Object, requiring casting, (4) Only forward traversal — cannot go backwards, (5) Only works with legacy collections (Vector, Hashtable, Properties).\n\nIterator (java.util.Iterator): Introduced in Java 1.2 as part of the Collections Framework. Methods: hasNext() — checks if more elements exist, next() — returns the next element (generic E with Iterator<E>), remove() — removes the last element returned by next() (optional operation). Advantages: (1) Supports removal during iteration — remove() safely deletes the current element, (2) Fail-fast — throws ConcurrentModificationException if the collection is structurally modified during iteration (except via remove()), helping detect concurrent modification bugs early, (3) Generic — Iterator<E> provides type safety, no casting needed, (4) Works with all modern collections (List, Set, Map via entrySet), (5) Shorter method names (hasNext/next vs hasMoreElements/nextElement).\n\nListIterator (java.util.ListIterator): Extends Iterator with bidirectional traversal and modification capabilities. Additional methods: hasPrevious()/previous() — traverse backwards, nextIndex()/previousIndex() — get index positions, add(E) — insert element, set(E) — replace the last element returned. Only available for List implementations.\n\nBest practice: Always use Iterator or ListIterator. Use Enumeration only when interfacing with legacy APIs.", code:`// Enumeration (legacy)\nVector<String> v=new Vector<>();\nEnumeration<String> e=v.elements();\nwhile(e.hasMoreElements()) e.nextElement();\n\n// Iterator (modern)\nIterator<String> it=list.iterator();\nwhile(it.hasNext()) { it.next(); it.remove(); }`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Enumeration: legacy, hasMoreElements/nextElement, no remove, not fail-fast. Iterator: modern, hasNext/next/remove, fail-fast. ListIterator: add/set/previous/indices. Always prefer Iterator/ListIterator." },
      { id:"m13", question:"What is the difference between HashMap and Hashtable?", answer:"HashMap and Hashtable are both Map implementations that store key-value pairs, but Hashtable is a legacy class that has been superseded by HashMap and ConcurrentHashMap.\n\nHashMap (Java 1.2): The standard, modern map implementation. Not thread-safe — no synchronization overhead, making it significantly faster. Allows one null key and multiple null values — useful for sentinel mappings. Uses hash table with buckets and linked lists (and red-black trees since Java 8 for buckets with >8 entries). Fail-fast iterators — throw ConcurrentModificationException if the map is structurally modified during iteration. Initial capacity 16, load factor 0.75. Should be used in single-threaded contexts or when external synchronization is provided.\n\nHashtable (Java 1.0): The original map implementation from Java 1.0. All methods are synchronized — thread-safe but slow (every operation acquires a lock, even reads). Does NOT allow null keys or null values — throws NullPointerException. Also uses hash table but without the tree optimization for collision buckets. Not recommended for any modern code.\n\nWhy Hashtable is obsolete: The synchronized methods provide coarse-grained locking — every operation locks the entire map, which means only one thread can access the map at a time (even for reads). This creates severe contention in multi-threaded applications. ConcurrentHashMap (Java 5) provides much better thread safety with fine-grained locking (segment-level or bucket-level locks) — multiple threads can read and write concurrently without blocking each other.\n\nDecision guide: Single-threaded → HashMap. Multi-threaded → ConcurrentHashMap. Never use Hashtable. If you need a synchronized wrapper for HashMap: Collections.synchronizedMap(hashMap), but ConcurrentHashMap is still preferred.", code:`Map<String,Integer> hm=new HashMap<>(); // not thread-safe\nhm.put(null,1); // OK\nMap<String,Integer> ht=new Hashtable<>(); // thread-safe\nht.put(null,1); // NullPointerException!`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"HashMap: modern, not synchronized, allows null, fail-fast iterator. Hashtable: legacy (Java 1.0), all methods synchronized, no null, not recommended. For thread-safe map: use ConcurrentHashMap instead of Hashtable." },
      { id:"m14", question:"What is the difference between Vector and ArrayList?", answer:"Vector and ArrayList are both resizable array implementations of the List interface, but Vector is a legacy class with synchronization overhead that makes it unsuitable for modern use.\n\nArrayList (Java 1.2): The standard, modern dynamic array implementation. Not synchronized — no thread-safety overhead, making it significantly faster than Vector in single-threaded contexts. Grows by 50% when capacity is exceeded: newCapacity = oldCapacity + (oldCapacity >> 1). Supports RandomAccess marker interface — indicates O(1) index-based access. Fail-fast iterators. Allows adding null elements. The default choice for any List in single-threaded code.\n\nVector (Java 1.0): The original dynamic array from Java 1.0. All methods are synchronized — thread-safe but slow because every operation (even reads) acquires the object lock. Grows by 100% (doubles) when capacity is exceeded: newCapacity = 2 * oldCapacity. Also supports RandomAccess. The larger growth factor means Vector allocates more memory per resize but resizes less frequently. Extends the legacy Vector class which has methods not in the List interface (addElement, elementAt, insertElementAt).\n\nPerformance impact of synchronization: Vector's synchronized methods mean every call (get, set, add, size, etc.) acquires and releases the object's intrinsic lock. In a single-threaded application, this is pure overhead — the lock is never contended, but the acquisition/release still costs CPU cycles. Benchmarks show ArrayList is 2-3x faster than Vector for single-threaded operations.\n\nThread-safe alternatives: If you need a thread-safe list, don't use Vector. Instead: (1) Collections.synchronizedList(arrayList) — wraps ArrayList with synchronized methods, (2) CopyOnWriteArrayList — thread-safe list optimized for read-heavy scenarios (creates a copy on each write), (3) Explicit synchronization with synchronized blocks around critical sections.\n\nBest practice: Always use ArrayList unless you specifically need thread safety, in which case use CopyOnWriteArrayList or synchronized collections.", code:`List<String> al=new ArrayList<>(); // not synchronized, faster\nList<String> v=new Vector<>();     // synchronized, slower\n// Both: dynamic array, random access O(1)`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Vector: Java 1.0, all methods synchronized, 2x growth. ArrayList: Java 1.2, not synchronized, 1.5x growth. For thread-safe list: Collections.synchronizedList() or CopyOnWriteArrayList. ArrayList preferred in most cases." },
      { id:"m15", question:"What are wrapper classes? Why needed?", answer:"Wrapper classes are object representations of Java's eight primitive types. Each primitive has a corresponding wrapper class in java.lang that encapsulates the primitive value in an object. This duality exists because Java is both a primitive-oriented language (for performance) and an object-oriented language (for generality).\n\nThe 8 wrapper classes: int→Integer, byte→Byte, short→Short, long→Long, float→Float, double→Double, char→Character, boolean→Boolean. All numeric wrappers (Integer, Long, Double, etc.) extend java.lang.Number. Character and Boolean extend Object directly. All wrappers are immutable and final.\n\nWhy wrapper classes are needed: (1) Collections require objects — you can't create List<int> or Map<int, String>. You must use List<Integer> and Map<Integer, String>. (2) Generics only work with objects — type parameters must be reference types, not primitives. (3) Utility methods — wrappers provide conversion methods: Integer.parseInt('42'), Double.parseDouble('3.14'), Integer.valueOf('FF', 16). (4) Constants — wrappers define MIN_VALUE, MAX_VALUE, SIZE, BYTES. (5) Type conversion — methods like intValue(), longValue(), doubleValue() convert between numeric types.\n\nAutoboxing and Unboxing (Java 5): The compiler automatically converts between primitives and wrappers. Autoboxing: primitive → wrapper — Integer i = 42; is compiled as Integer i = Integer.valueOf(42);. Unboxing: wrapper → primitive — int n = i; is compiled as int n = i.intValue();. This eliminates explicit conversion code but has performance implications — autoboxing creates objects and unboxing can throw NullPointerException.\n\nInteger cache: Integer caches instances for values -128 to 127 (by default). Integer.valueOf(42) returns the same cached object for all calls within this range. This means Integer a = 127; Integer b = 127; a == b is true (same object). But Integer c = 128; Integer d = 128; c == d is false (different objects). Always use .equals() for wrapper comparison, never ==.", code:`// Primitives → Wrappers\nint → Integer    char → Character\nbyte → Byte      long → Long\nshort → Short    float → Float\ndouble → Double  boolean → Boolean\n\n// Usage\nList<Integer> list=new ArrayList<>();\nlist.add(42); // autoboxing\nint val=Integer.parseInt("42");\nint max=Integer.MAX_VALUE;`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"8 wrappers in java.lang. All extend Number except Character and Boolean. Immutable. Integer caches -128 to 127. Provide utility methods: parseInt, valueOf, MAX_VALUE, MIN_VALUE. Required for Collections and generics." },
      { id:"m16", question:"What is the difference between aggregation and composition?", answer:"Aggregation and composition are two types of association relationships between objects in OOP, differing in the strength of the 'has-a' relationship and the lifecycle dependency between the whole and its parts.\n\nAggregation (Weak 'has-a'): Represents a relationship where the contained objects can exist independently of the container. The container 'has' the parts, but the parts are not destroyed when the container is destroyed. The lifecycle of the parts is independent — they can be shared between multiple containers and survive after the container is garbage collected. UML notation: empty diamond on the container side. Example: Department has Teachers — if the Department is dissolved, the Teachers still exist and can work in other departments. Implementation: Typically, the contained objects are passed to the container via constructor or setter (not created inside the container).\n\nComposition (Strong 'part-of'): Represents a relationship where the contained objects cannot exist independently of the container. The parts are created within and owned by the container, and they are destroyed when the container is destroyed. The lifecycle of the parts is dependent — they cannot be shared with other containers. UML notation: filled diamond on the container side. Example: House has Rooms — if the House is demolished, the Rooms cease to exist. A Room cannot belong to two Houses. Implementation: Typically, the contained objects are created inside the container's constructor and not exposed to outside code (no setter for the parts).\n\nKey differences: (1) Lifecycle dependency: Aggregation — independent; Composition — dependent, (2) Ownership: Aggregation — shared reference; Composition — exclusive ownership, (3) Creation: Aggregation — parts created externally, passed in; Composition — parts created internally by the container, (4) Deletion: Aggregation — parts survive container deletion; Composition — parts are deleted with the container, (5) Sharing: Aggregation — parts can be shared; Composition — parts belong to one container only.", code:`// Aggregation — weak ownership\nclass Department { List<Teacher> teachers; }\n// Teacher exists without Department\n\n// Composition — strong ownership\nclass House { List<Room> rooms; }\n// Room doesn't exist without House`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Aggregation: 'has-a', independent lifecycle, represented by empty diamond in UML. Composition: 'part-of', dependent lifecycle, filled diamond in UML. In composition, destroying whole destroys parts. In aggregation, parts survive." },
      { id:"m17", question:"What is the instanceof operator?", answer:"The instanceof operator is a binary operator in Java that tests whether an object is an instance of a specific type (class, subclass, or interface implementation). It returns a boolean — true if the object is an instance, false otherwise. It's the safe way to check an object's runtime type before performing a cast.\n\nBehavior: obj instanceof Type returns true if obj is: (1) An instance of Type itself, (2) An instance of any subclass of Type, (3) An instance of any class that implements Type (if Type is an interface), (4) null instanceof Type always returns false — null is not an instance of any type, not even Object. This makes instanceof null-safe — no NullPointerException.\n\nCommon uses: (1) Type checking before casting: if (obj instanceof String) { String s = (String) obj; } — prevents ClassCastException, (2) Implementing equals(): if (!(obj instanceof MyClass)) return false; — standard pattern, (3) Polymorphic dispatch in frameworks that can't use virtual methods, (4) Type-based conditional logic.\n\nJava 16+ Pattern Matching for instanceof: The old pattern requires two steps — check and cast. Pattern matching combines them: if (obj instanceof String s) { // s is already cast, use directly System.out.println(s.length()); }. The variable s is in scope within the if block and is already of type String — no explicit cast needed. The compiler infers that within the if block, obj is guaranteed to be a String.\n\nBest practice: Don't overuse instanceof — it often indicates a design problem. If you find yourself checking types and performing different actions, consider: (1) Polymorphism — override a method in each subclass instead of checking types, (2) Visitor pattern — for complex type-based operations, (3) Strategy pattern — encapsulate type-specific behavior. Use instanceof when: implementing equals(), working with frameworks that give you Object, or when polymorphism isn't feasible.", code:`Animal a=new Dog();\na instanceof Dog;    // true\na instanceof Animal;  // true\na instanceof Object;  // true\na instanceof Cat;     // false\n\n// Java 16+ pattern matching\nif(a instanceof Dog d) {\n    d.bark(); // d already cast\n}`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"instanceof: tests type at runtime, includes subclasses. null instanceof X always false. Java 16+: pattern variable `if(obj instanceof Type var)` — combines check and cast. Don't overuse—polymorphism is often better." },
      { id:"m18", question:"What is the difference between object cloning and object copying?", answer:"Object cloning and object copying are two approaches to creating a duplicate of an object, differing in mechanism, type safety, and best practices.\n\nObject Cloning (via clone()): Uses the Cloneable interface and Object.clone() method. The clone() method is protected in Object, so you must override it as public. It creates a new instance without calling any constructor and performs a shallow field-by-field copy. For deep copy, you must manually clone each mutable reference field inside your override. The return type is Object, requiring an explicit cast. Cloning is fraught with issues: (1) Cloneable is a marker interface with no methods — confusing contract, (2) clone() doesn't call constructors — can break class invariants, (3) Shallow copy by default — dangerous for mutable fields, (4) Requires CloneNotSupportedException handling or suppression, (5) Doesn't work well with final fields (can't assign to final field after construction), (6) The Cloneable-clone contract is considered broken (Joshua Bloch, Effective Java Item 13).\n\nObject Copying (via copy constructor or factory method): Creates a new object by calling a constructor (or static factory) that takes an instance of the same class as a parameter and copies its fields. Example: Student(Student other) { this.name = other.name; this.address = new Address(other.address); }. Advantages: (1) Simple and familiar — just a constructor, no special interfaces or methods, (2) Type-safe — no casting needed (returns the exact type), (3) Works with final fields — constructor can assign to final fields, (4) Deep copy is natural — you control exactly what gets copied and how, (5) No exception handling needed — no CloneNotSupportedException, (6) Can choose between shallow and deep copy per field, (7) Can validate and transform during copying, (8) Works with inheritance — subclass copy constructors can call super(other).\n\nJoshua Bloch's recommendation: 'Provide a copy constructor or copy factory instead of clone.' The copy constructor pattern is simpler, safer, and more flexible than the Cloneable/clone mechanism. The only advantage of clone() is that it can copy arrays efficiently (System.arraycopy).", code:`// Clone\nclass Student implements Cloneable {\n    String name;\n    protected Object clone() { return super.clone(); }\n}\nStudent s2=(Student)s1.clone();\n\n// Copy constructor (preferred)\nclass Student {\n    String name;\n    Student(Student other) { this.name=other.name; }\n}\nStudent s2=new Student(s1);`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"Clone: Cloneable interface, clone() method, shallow by default. Copy constructor: simpler, type-safe, no Cloneable needed, handles deep copy easily. Most developers prefer copy constructor over clone. Joshua Bloch: 'clone is broken'." },
      { id:"m19", question:"What is the difference between String join() and StringJoiner?", answer:"String.join() and StringJoiner are both Java 8 features for joining strings with a delimiter, but they serve different complexity levels.\n\nString.join() (static method): A simple, one-shot utility for joining strings. It's a static method on the String class that takes a delimiter and either varargs or an Iterable/CharSequence array. It joins all elements in a single call — no incremental building. Use cases: Quick one-liners where you have all elements available at once. Example: String.join(',', 'A', 'B', 'C') → 'A,B,C'. Or with a collection: String.join('-', listOfStrings). Limitations: No prefix or suffix, no incremental addition, no empty-value handling customization.\n\nStringJoiner (class): A more flexible, builder-pattern class for constructing joined strings incrementally. You create a StringJoiner with a delimiter, optionally a prefix and suffix, then call add() for each element. The elements are accumulated and joined only when toString() is called. Use cases: When you need prefix/suffix, when elements are added incrementally (e.g., inside a loop), when you need to customize the representation of empty joiners. Example: new StringJoiner(', ', '[', ']').add('A').add('B').add('C').toString() → '[A, B, C]'. Key features: (1) Prefix and suffix: new StringJoiner(delimiter, prefix, suffix), (2) Empty value: setEmptyValue('none') — what to return when no elements have been added (instead of prefix+suffix), (3) Incremental building: add elements one at a time via add() or merge() another StringJoiner, (4) Used internally by Collectors.joining() — when you call stream.collect(Collectors.joining(', ', '[', ']')), it creates a StringJoiner internally.\n\nWhen to use which: Use String.join() for simple cases — you have all elements, no prefix/suffix needed. Use StringJoiner when you need prefix/suffix, incremental addition, or custom empty-value handling. In streams, use Collectors.joining() which wraps StringJoiner.", code:`// String.join — simple\nString s=String.join(",", "A","B","C"); // "A,B,C"\n\n// StringJoiner — customizable\nStringJoiner sj=new StringJoiner(", ", "[", "]");\nsj.add("A").add("B").add("C");\nString result=sj.toString(); // "[A, B, C]"`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"String.join: quick one-liner, varargs or Iterable. StringJoiner: builder pattern, prefix/suffix, add incrementally. StringJoiner used internally by Collectors.joining(). Use join for simple cases, StringJoiner for prefix/suffix." },
      { id:"m20", question:"What is the Java Module System? (Java 9)", answer:"The Java Platform Module System (JPMS), introduced in Java 9 as part of Project Jigsaw, is a fundamental change to how Java code is organized, packaged, and encapsulated. It extends the access control model beyond classes and packages to include modules — groups of packages with explicit dependencies and well-defined public APIs.\n\nmodule-info.java: Every module must have a module-info.java file at its root that declares the module's name, dependencies, and public API. This file is compiled into module-info.class and is the module's descriptor.\n\nKey directives: (1) requires moduleName — declares a dependency on another module. Without this, the module cannot access the other module's exported packages. (2) requires transitive moduleName — declares a dependency that is also exposed to modules that depend on this module. If A requires transitive B, and C requires A, then C can also access B's exported packages. (3) exports packageName — makes the package accessible to all modules. Only exported packages are visible outside the module; all other packages are strongly encapsulated. (4) exports packageName to moduleName — qualified export — makes the package accessible only to specified modules. (5) opens packageName — allows reflective access to the package (needed for frameworks like Spring, Hibernate that use reflection). Without opens, reflection into non-exported packages fails. (6) opens packageName to moduleName — qualified open — reflective access only for specified modules. (7) uses and provides — for service loading (ServiceLoader integration).\n\nBenefits: (1) Strong encapsulation: Non-exported packages are truly inaccessible — no more accessing internal APIs (sun.misc.Unsafe, com.sun.tools.javac.*) from outside the module. (2) Reliable configuration: Dependencies are explicit — the JVM verifies all requires at startup. Missing dependencies cause ModuleResolutionException, not runtime errors. (3) Custom runtime images: jlink creates a minimal JRE containing only the modules your application needs — dramatically reduces deployment size (from ~200MB JRE to ~30MB custom image). (4) Better security: Internal APIs can't be accessed, reducing the attack surface.\n\nChallenges: (1) Migration effort: Existing code must be modularized or run as unnamed/automatic modules, (2) Split packages: Two modules cannot contain the same package — causes conflict, (3) Reflection restrictions: Frameworks using reflection need opens directives, (4) Classpath vs modulepath: The old classpath mechanism still works but bypasses module encapsulation.", code:`// module-info.java\nmodule com.myapp {\n    requires java.sql;           // dependency\n    requires transitive java.base; // transitive\n    exports com.myapp.api;       // public API\n    // com.myapp.internal not exported (encapsulated)\n}\n\n// Benefits:\n// - Strong encapsulation (no reflection into non-exported)\n// - Reliable dependency management\n// - Smaller deployment with jlink`, codeLanguage:"java", explanation:"module: group of packages. requires: dependencies. exports: public packages. opens: reflection access. transitive: dependency propagation. Benefits: strong encapsulation, reliable config, custom runtime (jlink). Challenges: migration effort, split packages, reflection restrictions." },
    ],
  },
];
